		<item>
		<title>How TIME and Statista Determined Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7377673/asia-pacifics-best-companies-2026-methodology/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[TIME Staff]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 14:17:18 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Companies]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7377673</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[TIME has published its annual list of Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies, in partnership with Statista, a leading international provider of market and consumer data and rankings. The result of this quantitative study: 500 companies shaping the Asia-Pacific region&#8217;s role in global business. Here&#8217;s how the winners were selected. Methodology The &#8220;Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026&#8221; ranking&#8230;]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7377673"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7377673/asia-pacifics-best-companies-2026-methodology/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Best-Companies-Asia-Pacific-2026.jpg" alt=""/>



<p>TIME has published its annual list of <a href="https://time.com/collection/worlds-best-companies-2025-asia-pacific/" ><a href="https://time.com/7377459/asia-pacific-best-companies-2026/">Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies</a></a>, in partnership with Statista, a leading international provider of market and consumer data and rankings. The result of this quantitative study: 500 companies shaping the Asia-Pacific region&#8217;s role in global business. Here&#8217;s how the winners were selected.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Methodology</h2>



<p>The &#8220;<a href="https://time.com/7377459/asia-pacific-best-companies-2026/" >Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</a>&#8221; ranking is a comprehensive analysis aimed to identify the top performing companies in the Asia-Pacific region. The ranking focuses on three key dimensions: Employee Satisfaction, Financial Performance, and Sustainability Transparency (ESG).</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>The first dimension, Employee Satisfaction, was evaluated using survey data from 2024 from employees worldwide with a main focus on the Asia-Pacific region. The surveys were conducted across the Asia-Pacific region with data collected from more than 50,000 participants. The evaluation encompassed evaluations of companies based on direct and indirect recommendations.</p>



<p>The second dimension, Financial Performance, was assessed using data from Statista&rsquo;s financial database and targeted research. The companies had to meet certain criteria to be considered for the evaluation, including generating a revenue of at least US $100 million in 2024. Companies also needed to either demonstrate positive revenue growth from 2022 to 2024 or generate a profit in 2024. Both relative and absolute growth were considered in the evaluation.</p>



<p>The third dimension, Sustainability Transparency, was evaluated based on ESG data among standardized KPIs from Statista&rsquo;s ESG Database and targeted data research. To formulate a comprehensive ESG index, multiple Key Performance Indicators were collected. For the environmental evaluation, this included the 2023 carbon emissions intensity and reduction rate compared to 2021, as well as the Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP) score. The social dimension assessed the share of women on the board of directors and the existence of a human rights policy. The governance dimension evaluated whether a company had a Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) report adhering to the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) guidelines and a compliance or anti- corruption guideline.</p>



<p>Once the data was collected and evaluated, it was consolidated and weighted within a scoring model. The scores of all three dimensions were added on an equal percentage basis to form the final ranking score of a maximum of 100 points. The 500 companies with the highest scores were awarded as the <a href="https://time.com/7377459/asia-pacific-best-companies-2026/" >Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</a> by TIME and Statista.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7377673</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7377459/asia-pacific-best-companies-2026/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chad de Guzman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 14:15:29 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Companies]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7377459</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Anxiety gripped global markets when Donald Trump returned to the White House last year. But a year on, despite the U.S. President&#8217;s game-changing policies, much of the Asia-Pacific region appears to have insulated itself from the shocks, with businesses and economies changing tactics to rely less on the U.S. Banking and financial services once again&#8230;]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7377459"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7377459/asia-pacific-best-companies-2026/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Best-Companies-Asia-Pacific-2026.jpg" alt=""/>



<p>Anxiety gripped global markets when Donald Trump returned to the White House last year. But a year on, despite the U.S. President&rsquo;s game-changing policies, much of the Asia-Pacific region appears to have insulated itself from the shocks, with businesses and economies changing tactics to rely less on the U.S.</p>



<p>Banking and financial services once again dominate the latest statistical ranking of 500 of the region&rsquo;s best companies conducted by TIME and <a href="https://r.statista.com/en/licensing/worlds-best-companies-2023/award/"  target="_blank">Statista</a>, which assesses firms using three key metrics: employee satisfaction, revenue growth, and environmental, social, and governance (ESG) evaluations. While 2025 started rocky with Trump&rsquo;s tariff war, the Asia-Pacific region stabilized towards the yearend, says Daniel Kritenbrink, formerly U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs and now partner at The Asia Group. &ldquo;Compared to earlier in 2025, most businesses face a slightly more clear, stable, and certain business environment that they can plan around,&rdquo; he says.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p><strong>Methodology: <a href="https://time.com/7377673/asia-pacifics-best-companies-2026-methodology/" >How TIME and Statista Determined Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</a></strong></p>



<p>Of this cohort&rsquo;s top 10, five are from the banking sector, with Singapore&rsquo;s DBS Bank keeping the top spot from last year, followed by Australia&rsquo;s Commonwealth Bank. Both firms reported profitability&mdash;despite the volatile macroeconomic environment&mdash;and wide adoptions of AI in their practices. Rounding out the top 10 is the Philippines&rsquo; Bank of the Philippine Islands, the country&rsquo;s best-performing company on the list.</p>



<p>The financial sector has a rosy outlook for 2026, says Taimur Baig, chief economist and managing director at DBS Bank, signaled by initial public offerings from Hong Kong and Singapore reviving moribund regional capital markets, and rallying bank stocks. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s an expectation of equity capital markets catching tailwind,&rdquo; Baig says. He expects market confidence will increase, allowing companies to take higher risks&mdash;including in the artificial intelligence sector&mdash;which means more business for banks.</p>



<p>The automotive industry, a victim of Trump&rsquo;s aggressive tariffs, survived through persistent EV demand. Toyota&mdash;which retained its world&rsquo;s top-selling automaker status this year thanks to strong U.S. sales of hybrid vehicles&mdash;ranked third in the list, followed by Hyundai (no. 8) and Honda (no. 12). Chinese companies Xiaomi (no. 23), BYD (no. 43), and Geely (no. 60)&mdash;also known for their EV offerings&mdash;similarly made the cut. Xiaomi is China&rsquo;s best-performing business this year, as the second-largest economy faces ongoing domestic struggles in automotive sales, and its overproduction is spilling into other nations.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The insurance, healthcare, and social services sector also performed well, and are projected to sustain expansion, with the Asia-Pacific region anticipated to boost global life insurance premium volumes. The list includes Australia&rsquo;s QBE Insurance Group (no. 7), AIA Group in Hong Kong (no. 15), and SBI Life Insurance from India (no.19).&nbsp;</p>



<p>Region-specific growths are also evident: of the top 10 companies, four are from Australia, whose sluggish economy slightly recovered in 2025. Alicia Garc&iacute;a-Herrero, chief economist for Asia-Pacific at French financial services firm Natixis, says that Australia &ldquo;delivered consistency rather than fireworks&rdquo; with its strong financials and its cornerstone mining industry. She also points to select strengths in the pharmaceutical, medical technology, and consumer goods sectors; Australia&rsquo;s largest retailer of consumer goods, Woolworths, ranks sixth in the list.</p>



<p>Zooming out, however, Indian firms form the lion&rsquo;s share, taking up 179 spots in the list. But Garc&iacute;a-Herrero notes that India shining as a &ldquo;bright spot&rdquo; on the market does not necessarily indicate outstanding performance. The country saw periods of high volatility, with <a href="https://www.cnbctv18.com/market/foreign-investors-may-return-to-india-but-not-everyone-is-convinced-it-matters-alpha-article-19841548.htm"  target="_blank">foreign investment outflow</a> amid a weak rupee and tariffs, though India still managed to <a href="https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/1102431/ado-december-2025.pdf"  target="_blank">pull regional economic forecasts</a> upward due to robust domestic consumption. </p>



<p>India is expected to edge out Japan in the race for the world&rsquo;s fourth-largest economy title, but the two nations <a href="https://www.mea.gov.in/bilateral-documents.htm?dtl%2F40066%2FFact+Sheet++IndiaJapan+Economic+Security+Cooperation"  target="_blank">ramped up</a> their economic partnership last year, focusing on the semiconductor, clean energy, critical minerals, and information and communications technology sectors. Three Japanese companies on the list&mdash;Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group (no. 4), Mizuho Financial Group (no. 17), and MUFG (no. 52)&mdash;have also expanded into India&rsquo;s financial services, betting on the South Asian market&rsquo;s rapid growth. Overall, recalibration became the year&rsquo;s business buzzword for Asia-Pacific, and with Trump thrusting the world into more uncertainty, players in the region sought solutions in bilateral and multilateral cooperation beyond the U.S.</p>



<p><strong>Methodology: <a href="https://time.com/7377673/asia-pacifics-best-companies-2026-methodology/" >How TIME and Statista Determined Asia-Pacific&#8217;s Best Companies of 2026</a></strong></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-wp-embed is-provider-datawrapper wp-block-embed-datawrapper"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe class="wp-embedded-content" sandbox="allow-scripts" security="restricted" title="TIME Asia-Pacific&#039;s Best Companies of 2026" src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/hYtuP/2/#?secret=6hCvWj9TBQ" data-secret="6hCvWj9TBQ" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" height="5968"></iframe>
</div></figure>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7377459</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Trump Threatens to Block Opening of Bridge Between U.S. and Canada, Demands Compensation</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7377319/trump-threatens-canada-ontario-michigan-bridge/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Callum Sutherland]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 Feb 2026 13:43:10 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7377319</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[One Canadian official has referred to Trump's threat as "insane."]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7377319"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7377319/trump-threatens-canada-ontario-michigan-bridge/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/GettyImages-2240467708.jpg" alt="EGYPT-US-ISRAEL-PALESTINIAN-CONFLICT-TRUMP"/>



<p>President Donald Trump has threatened to block the opening of a $4.7 billion bridge connecting Detroit, Michigan, to Windsor, Ontario, in the latest display of frayed relations between the U.S. and Canada.</p>



<p>In a lengthy social media post, Trump raised a number of issues against his northern neighbor and doubled down on his often-cited claim that Canada has &ldquo;treated the United States very unfairly for decades.&rdquo;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>The President claimed that Canada will own both sides of the Gordie Howe International Bridge, for which construction <a href="https://gordiehoweinternationalbridge.com/project/our-story/"  target="_blank">began</a> in 2018 and is nearing completion, and complained that the infrastructure has been built with &ldquo;virtually no U.S. content.&rdquo;</p>



<p>After accusing Ontario of refusing to stock some U.S.-produced alcoholic products in shops and complaining about Canada&#8217;s tariffs on dairy products, Trump declared he will &ldquo;not allow this bridge to open until the United States is fully compensated&rdquo; for everything it has &ldquo;given&rdquo; to Canada.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We will start negotiations immediately,&rdquo; he warned. &ldquo;With all that we have given them, we should own, perhaps, at least one half of this asset.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney on Tuesday told reporters he had spoken with Trump about a number of topics, including the bridge. &ldquo;I explained that Canada, of course, paid for the construction of the bridge, over $4 billion. That the ownership is shared between the state of Michigan and the government of Canada,&rdquo; Carney said. He pushed back against Trump&#8217;s claims about the building materials, arguing that both Canadian and U.S. steel had been used. The Prime Minister went on to say the &ldquo;situation will be settled,&rdquo; but offered no further details.</p>



<p>Carney&#8217;s response points to the <a href="https://gordiehoweinternationalbridge.com/the-canada-michigan-crossing-agreement/"  target="_blank">Canada-Michigan Crossing Agreement</a>, signed in June 2012, which states that the Canadian government will pay for the bridge, and use toll funds&mdash;collected over 30 years&mdash;as reimbursement.</p>



<p>The agreement also stipulates that the bridge, named after prolific Canadian ice hockey player Gordie Howe, will be publicly owned by the governments of Canada and Michigan, and all iron and steel used in construction will be sourced from either the U.S. or Canada. The offer from the Canadian government to cover most of the costs was accepted by Michigan&#8217;s then-Gov. Rick Snyder.</p>



<p>All seemed to be going well in February 2017, when Trump and then-Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau released <a href="https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefings-statements/joint-statement-president-donald-j-trump-prime-minister-justin-trudeau/"  target="_blank">a joint statement,</a> celebrating the project and calling the crossing &ldquo;a vital economic link between our two countries.&rdquo;</p>



<p>More recently, the U.S. Department of Homeland Security (DHS) <a href="https://assets.aila.org/files/646f12ba-d503-4e8f-949c-d1ef1d47e135/26020202.pdf?1770050442"  target="_blank">published a rule</a> on Jan. 30, declaring the bridge will serve as an official port of entry. It said the crossing will save $12.7 million annually for travelers, in part by reducing congestion.</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s new threat to suspend the bridge&rsquo;s opening has prompted criticism among Canadian officials.</p>



<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just insane. When I read that post, I really can&#8217;t believe what I&#8217;m reading,&rdquo; Mayor of Windsor Drew Dilkens <a href="https://www.cbc.ca/player/play/video/9.7082187"  target="_blank">told</a> CBC, adding that the bridge should create an opportunity &ldquo;where a Prime Minister would meet a President in the middle, they would shake hands, and they would celebrate this victory for two nations. Unfortunately, Donald Trump has created an environment where I don&#8217;t think that is going to happen in the near term.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Michigan Democrats have also criticized Trump&#8217;s statement regarding the multibillion dollar project.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The Gordie Howe Bridge is an incredibly important infrastructure project for Michigan. President Trump&#8217;s threat tonight to tank it is awful for our state&#8217;s economy,&rdquo; <a href="https://x.com/SenatorSlotkin/status/2021013398129877408"  target="_blank">said</a> Sen. Elissa Slotkin. Canceling this project will have serious repercussions. Higher costs for Michigan businesses, less secure supply chains, and ultimately, fewer jobs.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Slotkin argued that Trump&#8217;s threat is merely &ldquo;punishing Michiganders for a trade war he started&rdquo; and, in reference to Canada&#8217;s recent talks with China, went on to say: &ldquo;the only reason Canada is on the verge of a trade deal with China is because President Trump has kicked them in the teeth for a year.&rdquo;</p>



<p>TIME has reached out to the White House for comment.</p>



<p>Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer also expressed the importance of the construction efforts.</p>



<p>&ldquo;This project has been a tremendous example of bipartisan and international cooperation. It&#8217;s going to open one way or another, and the Governor looks forward to attending the ribbon cutting,&rdquo; said Whitmer&rsquo;s office in a statement to TIME.</p>



<p>However, some Michigan Republicans have come out in support of Trump. The state&#8217;s House Speaker Matt Hall echoed the President&#8217;s argument about U.S.-Canada relations.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Canada should treat us better and offer fair trade terms, especially when it comes to American farmers and liquor producers being unfairly targeted and having their products taken off of Canadian shelves,&rdquo; Hall said in a statement to TIME. &ldquo;President Trump is using the right leverage points to renegotiate better agreements&#8230; he will make sure Michigan and the United States come out ahead.&rdquo;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/GettyImages-2210333398.jpg" alt="Spanning the Detroit River, the Gordie H" alignment="original-size-image"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s frustration over the bridge marks the latest tension between the President and Canada.</p>



<p>At the World Economic Forum in Davos in January, Trump told attendees that Canada &ldquo;lives because of the United States.&rdquo; In a filmed address from Qu&eacute;bec City, <a href="https://time.com/7357333/carney-trump-row-united-states-canada-relationship/" >Carney responded to the claim</a>, firmly stating: &ldquo;Canada does not live because of the United States. Canada thrives because we are Canadian.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump had lashed out at Canada after taking umbrage at Carney&#8217;s own Davos speech, during which he boldly stated that the old world order is &ldquo;not coming back.&rdquo; He encouraged people not to &ldquo;mourn&rdquo; the way things used to be and advised that &ldquo;nostalgia is not a strategy.&rdquo; Carney urged middle powers to stand up for themselves, accusing &ldquo;great powers&rdquo; of using economic pressure to yield results.</p>



<p>While he did not name the U.S. or its President, Carney&#8217;s speech came in the midst of Trump attempting to acquire Greenland and after long-repeated threats to annex Canada and make it the &ldquo;<a href="https://time.com/7297490/trump-plan-to-annex-canada-51st-state-mark-carney/" >51st state</a>.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Carney has since explored alternative trade alliances and avenues for Canada. After traveling to Beijing last month to meet with Chinese President Xi Jinping, he announced that Canada and China had forged a &ldquo;<a href="https://www.pm.gc.ca/en/news/news-releases/2026/01/16/prime-minister-carney-forges-new-strategic-partnership-peoples"  target="_blank">new strategic partnership</a>&rdquo; focused on &ldquo;energy, agri-food, and trade.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump lashed out at the alliance while threatening the opening of the bridge, claiming China &ldquo;will eat Canada alive,&rdquo; leaving the U.S. with &ldquo;the leftovers.&rdquo; In a nod to the bridge&#8217;s namesake, he went on to predict that China will &ldquo;terminate all ice hockey being played in Canada, and permanently eliminate The Stanley Cup.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7377319</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Why Jimmy Lai’s Sentencing in Hong Kong Strikes Fear in Taiwan</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7377260/jimmy-lai-sentence-national-security-hong-kong-china-taiwan/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chad de Guzman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 Feb 2026 09:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7377260</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Critics say Hong Kong’s civil liberties have eroded under China’s “one country, two systems” model. Is Taiwan next?]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7377260"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7377260/jimmy-lai-sentence-national-security-hong-kong-china-taiwan/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/jimmy-lai-taiwan.jpg" alt="Hong Kong activists and supporters gather in support of Hong Kong activist publisher Jimmy Lai in Taipei, Taiwan, on Feb. 10, 2026."/>



<p>When a Hong Kong court handed media tycoon and pro-democracy leader Jimmy Lai a two-decade jail term on national security grounds on Monday, his son called it a &ldquo;<a href="https://x.com/RidgeandFrost/status/2020777735811965028"  target="_blank">death sentence</a>&rdquo; given Lai&rsquo;s age, 78, and deteriorating health. Critics across the globe, meanwhile, have described the sentence as a death knell for a once more free Hong Kong&mdash;as well as a signal of what could be in store for other places China has its eye on, namely Taiwan.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>&ldquo;I believe that the way that China is treating Hong Kong is the way that it wants to treat Taiwan next, and beyond that, other countries,&rdquo; Mark Clifford, president of the Committee for Freedom in Hong Kong Foundation in the U.S., told TIME before the sentence was handed down.</p>



<p>A Human Rights Watch spokesperson summed up the sentiment to TIME on Monday: &ldquo;Today is Hong Kong, tomorrow, Taiwan.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Lai, a vocal critic of China&rsquo;s increasing influence over Hong Kong&mdash;a special administrative region of China since the U.K. handed it over in 1997&mdash;and repression of pro-democratic voices, particularly after the passage of a <a href="https://time.com/5867000/hong-kong-china-national-security-law-effect/" >sweeping national security law</a> in 2020, was convicted in December of two counts of &ldquo;conspiring to collude with foreign forces,&rdquo; as well as of conspiring to publish seditious materials, as the founder of the pro-democracy newspaper Apple Daily.</p>



<p>But while Hong Kong and Beijing authorities and media have backed Lai&rsquo;s sentence, Taiwan&mdash;the self-governed island which China claims sovereignty over&mdash;has condemned it. Taiwan&#8217;s Mainland Affairs Council said in a <a href="https://www.mac.gov.tw/News_Content.aspx?n=05B73310C5C3A632&amp;sms=1A40B00E4C745211&amp;s=213FAE969E5552FE"  target="_blank">statement</a> that Lai&#8217;s harsh sentence &ldquo;not only deprives him of his personal liberty and tramples on freedom of speech and press freedom, but also denies the people&rsquo;s basic right to hold those in power accountable.&#8221;</p>



<p>Taiwan President William Lai Ching-te <a href="https://x.com/ChingteLai/status/2021106841296736478"  target="_blank">posted on X</a> on Tuesday that Lai&rsquo;s sentencing &ldquo;exposes the Hong Kong national security law for what it is&mdash;a tool of political persecution under China&rsquo;s &lsquo;one country, two systems&rsquo; that tramples human rights &amp; freedom of press,&rdquo; and he called for the media mogul&rsquo;s release.</p>



<p>Steve Tsang, director of the SOAS China Institute in London, tells TIME that Lai&rsquo;s sentence would affirm to the Taiwanese government and its people that the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; principle currently governing Hong Kong &ldquo;is a future they cannot accept.&rdquo;</p>



<p>That system was actually designed with Taiwan in mind. Former Chinese leader <a href="https://www.mfa.gov.cn/eng/zy/wjls/3604_665547/202405/t20240531_11367561.html"  target="_blank">Deng Xiaoping</a> advanced the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; framework as a way for Taiwan to peacefully reunite with the mainland, while &ldquo;respect[ing] the realities and the existing system there.&rdquo; In a bid to make the principle more palatable to the Taiwanese government, China applied it to Hong Kong and Macau after the British and the Portuguese territories were ceded back to China in the late 1990s, allowing the so-called special administrative regions to operate with their own economic system and governments.&nbsp;</p>



<p>But <a href="https://time.com/5786776/hong-kong-joshua-wong-future-homeland/" >pro-democracy figures</a> have argued that local governance has grown increasingly aligned with the mainland as political dissidents have either been jailed or exiled, organizations have disbanded, and a free press dismantled.</p>



<p>&ldquo;You take a model that&rsquo;s intended for Taiwan, you try it out in Hong Kong, and we&rsquo;ve seen how it works out,&rdquo; Clifford told TIME on Monday, adding that the freedoms and autonomy China promised to Hong Kong and the international community under the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; framework have all but disappeared. &ldquo;Of course, Taiwan feels like it&rsquo;s next.&rdquo; </p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7377260</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Rolling Blackouts, Hospital Shortages: How the U.S. Oil Blockade Is Impacting Cuba</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7373215/cuba-us-blockade-oil-venezuela/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Philip Wang]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 21:02:46 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7373215</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[A total U.S. blockade on oil has caused a severe energy crisis across Cuba. ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7373215"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7373215/cuba-us-blockade-oil-venezuela/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/GettyImages-2258177076.jpg" alt="CUBA-ENERGY-BLACKOUT"/>



<p>A United States-imposed blockade on oil to <a href="https://time.com/7344661/cuba-trump-venezuela-oil-economy-crisis/" >Cuba</a> is causing a severe energy crisis on the island that has resulted in rolling blackouts, a strain on hospitals and the grounding of jets.</p>



<p>On Monday, Cuban aviation authorities notified international airlines that the country is running out of jet fuel and that refuelling services for airlines will be suspended for a month, according to data from the Federal Aviation Administration. Air Canada said it was suspending its service to the island as a result. </p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>It comes after President Donald Trump signed an executive order last month announcing that he would impose tariffs on any country that sells or provides oil to Cuba, which is run by a communist government that the Trump Administration would <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/americas/the-u-s-is-actively-seeking-regime-change-in-cuba-by-the-end-of-the-year-1d0f178a?gaa_at=eafs&amp;gaa_n=AWEtsqfD7nhTDrKn_16qb5KWi3zhda3cwzfZmLjUVci37o07fek9ad6MMRLBTljh0bc%3D&amp;gaa_ts=698a41c8&amp;gaa_sig=y3Q0RhpBghK250_qDtCo3G3ab8qU3S4nVwXK1H6pSG7mewy9h2tFYAJtG9XmUJA3xTzsXxiCg7EOoUoaEjrrgQ%3D%3D"  target="_blank">like to</a> replace.  </p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7344628/us-venezuela-trump-maduro-oil-drugs-war-explainer-questions-answered/" ><em>What&rsquo;s Happening With the U.S. and Venezuela, Explained</em></a></p>



<p>The island&rsquo;s economy was already struggling due to decades of U.S. sanctions, but things rapidly deteriorated in January when shipments were halted from its main supplier, Venezuela, following a U.S. military operation to depose President Nicolas Maduro.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Mexico, another oil supplier to Cuba, also announced on Monday that it was suspending its shipments after Trump threatened to impose tariffs on Mexican exports to the U.S.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The Financial <em>Times</em> <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/f15ac8c6-c76b-40a1-bb41-95abbed7d8aa"  target="_blank">reported</a> in late January that Cuba only has oil reserves that could last for &ldquo;15 to 20 days&rdquo; at the current level of demand. </p>



<p>Some medical facilities have also been severely impacted by the fuel shortages. Local media <a href="https://www.14ymedio.com/cuba/cuba-acerca-opcion-cero-suspenden_1_1123458.html"  target="_blank">reported</a> that some provincial hospitals have canceled surgeries and outpatient transfers. Critical medical supplies such as painkillers, gauze, and antibiotics are also unavailable.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The fuel shortage has also strained the country&#8217;s food supplies. Last week, the U.S. gave $6 million in humanitarian aid to the country, the State Department said. The supplies include rice, beans, pasta, cans of tuna and solar lamps that will be delivered by the Catholic Church and Caritas. Mexico is also <a href="https://x.com/SRE_mx/status/2020603217852424637"  target="_blank">sending</a> more than 814 tons of food and hygiene products to Cuba, which is scheduled to arrive in a few days.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>The United Nations warned last week that the &ldquo;vast majority of Cubans&rdquo; are being hit by rolling blackouts, and that the humanitarian collapse would &ldquo;worsen, and if not collapse, if its oil needs go unmet.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;The last two years have been quite tough,&rdquo; said Francisco Pichon, the most senior United Nations official in Cuba.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Prior to the oil blockade, the Caribbean island suffered from a withering economy due to its dwindling tourism business since the Covid-19 pandemic. Last year, Hurricane Melissa also swept Cuba&rsquo;s five provinces, displacing more than 735,000 people while destroying homes and basic infrastructure.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In recent days, as the energy crisis has worsened, the Cuban government has called for dialogue with the U.S. government. Foreign Minister Bruno Rodriguez on Monday denounced the &#8220;cruel aggression&#8221; of the United States, which he said was aimed at &#8220;breaking the political will of the Cuban people.&#8221;</p>



<p>&#8220;The situation is tough and will demand great sacrifice,&#8221; said Rodriguez, while reiterating Cuba&#8217;s &#8220;willingness to engage in dialogue&#8221;, though on its own terms without pressure.</p>



<p>Trump said in early February that the U.S. is engaging in diplomatic conversations with &ldquo;the highest people&rdquo; in Cuba.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;It doesn&#8217;t have to be a humanitarian crisis. I think they probably would come to us and want to make a deal,&rdquo; Trump said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s remarks came not long after Secretary Marco Rubio acknowledged that the U.S. would like to see the end of the communist regime in Cuba.<br><br>&ldquo;That doesn&#8217;t mean that we&#8217;re going to make a change, but we would love to see a change,&#8221; Rubio <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/rubio-rules-military-action-venezuela-now/story?id=129637763"  target="_blank">told</a> a Congressional hearing late last month.<br><br>&#8220;There&#8217;s no doubt about the fact that it would be a great benefit to the United States if Cuba was no longer governed by an autocratic regime,&#8221; Rubio added.</p>



<p>Cuba&rsquo;s deputy foreign minister dismissed that possibility in an <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2026/02/04/tv/video/carlos-fernandez-de-cossio-cuba-amanpour"  target="_blank">interview</a> with CNN.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re not ready to discuss our constitutional system as we suppose the U.S. is not ready to discuss their constitutional system, their political system, their economic reality,&rdquo; Carlos Fern&aacute;ndez de Coss&iacute;o said.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
