		<item>
		<title>What Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul’s Election Means for Thailand and the World</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7373034/prime-minister-anutin-charnvirakul-thailand-election-result-bhumjaithai-interview-takeaways/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Charlie Campbell]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 05:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News desk edits]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7373034</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The incumbent Prime Minister’s conservative Bhumjaithai Party bested a progressive movement that had been surging for years but lost its shine amid rising nationalism and economic doldrums.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7373034"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7373034/prime-minister-anutin-charnvirakul-thailand-election-result-bhumjaithai-interview-takeaways/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/anutin-thailand-election-results.jpg" alt="Bhumjaithai Party Election Night Event"/>



<p>When TIME sat down with <a href="https://time.com/7364304/thailand-prime-minister-anutin-charnvirakul-election/" >Anutin Charnvirakul</a> late last month, Thailand&rsquo;s Prime Minister was feeling the strain of the campaign trail. The 59-year-old grumbled that gladhanding throngs of supporters in dusty villages had left him prey to bugs and viruses. &ldquo;I meet so many people and sometimes maybe they have caught a cold,&rdquo; Anutin said from Bangkok&rsquo;s neo-Gothic Government House. &ldquo;I hear them coughing and try to hold my breath. But I might not be able to do that 100%.&rdquo;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Still, Anutin held yet another rally that very evening, and the sacrifice appears to have paid off handsomely. His conservative Bhumjaithai Party won the most seats in Thailand&rsquo;s general election on Sunday, besting a progressive movement that had been surging for years but lost its shine amid rising nationalism and economic doldrums.</p>



<p>With 90% of the vote counted, Bhumjaithai had 194 seats of the 500-seat House of Representatives, with <a href="https://time.com/7317196/thailand-natthaphong-ruengpanyawut-peoples-party-election-profile/" >the progressive People&rsquo;s Party</a> coming second with 116 seats, per an Election Commission tally, meaning Anutin will almost certainly retain the Southeast Asia nation&rsquo;s top job, albeit as head of a coalition.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We will accept the decision of the people in giving us the confidence, the trust to the Bhumjaithai Party,&rdquo; Anutin told reporters at his party&rsquo;s headquarters in Bangkok late Sunday.</p>



<p>Here are five takeaways from TIME&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7364304/thailand-prime-minister-anutin-charnvirakul-election/" >sweeping interview</a> with Anutin regarding his plans for the nation of 70 million.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>1.</strong> <strong>Military influence here to stay</strong></h2>



<p>Anutin&rsquo;s victory capitalized on resurgent nationalism after months of <a href="https://time.com/7305413/thailand-cambodia-border-war-hun-sen-manet-paetongtarn-thaksin-shinawatra/" >bloody skirmishes between Thailand and Cambodia</a> over their disputed frontier. While the progressive movement campaigned on reducing the bloated military&rsquo;s role in politics and business, the border spat emboldened Anutin to portray himself as a hawkish patriot protecting national pride and security. However, he also talked up his good relationship with Cambodia&rsquo;s Prime Minister Hun Manet, whom he described as &ldquo;very intelligent and capable&rdquo; to TIME. &ldquo;I always had great respect for him.&rdquo;</p>



<p>While pinning blame on Cambodia for the bloodshed, Anutin spoke about the imperative to harmonize regional maps to permanently rectify the dispute. However, he declined to take back political authority on border security, which had been devolved to the military itself, empowering the brass hats full discretion to respond to perceived affronts with deadly force. &ldquo;Every move we would sit together and jointly decide, so we work as a team,&rdquo; says Anutin. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t have to bring back any authority.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>2.</strong> <strong>Progressive pain</strong></h2>



<p>The results were a blow to the People&rsquo;s Party, which was hoping to build on <a href="https://time.com/6310002/pita-limjaroenrat-thailand-move-forward-interview-profile/" >its predecessor Move Forward Party&rsquo;s electoral success</a> in 2023, when it secured a plurality 151 legislative seats. (However, it was blocked from forming a government by the Senate and then dissolved by the Constitutional Court.) While jingoistic support for the military was Anutin&rsquo;s secret weapon, the progressive&rsquo;s antagonist view of green uniforms turned out to be its kryptonite. Despite receiving the second largest number of votes, People&rsquo;s Party leader <a href="https://time.com/7317196/thailand-natthaphong-ruengpanyawut-peoples-party-election-profile/" >Natthaphong Ruengpanyawut</a> ruled out joining Bhumjaithai in government and instead vowed to hold Anutin&rsquo;s government to account in opposition. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t lose hope,&rdquo; Natthaphong told tearful supporters. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve come so far.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Certainly, Bhumjaithai&rsquo;s resounding victory provides grist for Anutin&rsquo;s argument that Thais are not hankering after radical reform as the progressives maintain. &ldquo;Division is actually from the media and the people who could not win,&rdquo; he told TIME. &ldquo;Rather than going back to improve themselves, they tend to blame other stuff.&rdquo;</p>



<p>However, alongside casting constituency and party ballots, Thais also voted in a referendum on whether to draft a new constitution, with preliminary tallies suggesting some 65% had voted in favor. How that new charter looks will be the next battleground, with progressives keen to amend sections on the <a href="https://time.com/6993473/thailand-2024-senate-election-results-democracy/" >establishment-stocked Senate</a> and royal prerogatives&mdash;but Anutin, in the driving seat, dead against.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>3.</strong> <strong>Resurgent royalism</strong></h2>



<p>Other than aligning with Thailand&rsquo;s armed forces, Anutin is also close to its sacrosanct royal palace, accompanying King Maha Vajiralongkorn during a four-day visit to Bhutan in April as well as his historic visit to China in November. In 2023, the Move Forward Party campaigned on curbing royal powers, though efforts to reform <a href="https://time.com/6296556/thailand-lese-majeste-reform-teen-crop-top/" >Thailand&rsquo;s draconian royal defamation law</a>, known as <em>l&egrave;se-majest&eacute;</em> or Article 112, were deemed unconstitutional and led to the party&rsquo;s dissolution by the Constitutional Court.</p>



<p>As such, the People&rsquo;s Party was <a href="https://time.com/7372530/thailand-election-lese-majeste-article-112-peoples-party-lookkate-bhumjaithai" >forced to sidestep this keystone issue in its latest campaign</a>. With the openly royalist Anutin receiving a strong mandate, you can expect efforts to curb royal powers to remain firmly on the backburner. Asked about his relationship with King Vajiralongkorn, Anutin told TIME: &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t dare have a relationship with any royal family member, but I&rsquo;m his humble servant.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>4.</strong> <strong>It&rsquo;s the economy, buffalo!</strong></h2>



<p>Thailand is already being branded the new &ldquo;<a href="https://www.nationthailand.com/news/general/40062291#:~:text=Thailand%20is%20increasingly%20being%20labelled,calls%20for%20deeper%20structural%20reform."  target="_blank">sick man of Asia</a>&rdquo; following years of torpid growth owed in large part to relentless political turmoil. (Its economy expanded by only 1.5% last year.) Anutin hopes that his resounding mandate can at least provide a modicum of stability while he enacts his pro-business agenda. He advocates creating new jobs by promoting industries from emerging global growth sectors, such as electric vehicles, medical and wellness services, bio-technology, and the digital economy.</p>



<p>But economists warn more structural reform is required to truly arrest Thailand&rsquo;s economic tailspin. This includes breaking up the monopolies&mdash;family-linked conglomerates dominate key sectors such as energy, retail, telecommunications, and food, with the top 5% of companies controlling over 85% of total revenue&mdash;something Anutin told TIME he is determined to tackle. But with such action against the interests of his elite backers, only time will tell whether he will truly walk the talk. &ldquo;Structural reform is never painless&mdash;but postponing it is far more costly,&rdquo; he says.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>5.</strong> <strong>Thailand to keep international balance act</strong></h2>



<p>Thailand is America&rsquo;s oldest ally in Asia while also boasts a thriving ethnically Chinese diaspora, including Anutin, whose ancestors hail from Guangdong province. However, Anutin also spent eight years studying and working in New York and feels a great affinity for the U.S. He says that Thailand refuses to take sides in this new era of Great Power competition.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We consistently stand by the rules-based international order and the norms agreed upon by the global community,&rdquo; he told TIME. &ldquo;In a polarized world, countries that remain pragmatic and reliable become more valuable, not less.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Anutin also wants to play a role within the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to bring a lasting peace to war-ravaged neighbor Myanmar, whose ruling junta recently underwent its own <a href="https://time.com/7357323/myanmar-election-junta-burma-explainer/" >election that has been widely condemned as a sham</a>. &ldquo;Engagement does not mean endorsement,&rdquo; Anutin says. &ldquo;We work with all sides to reduce suffering and support ASEAN-led solutions. Thailand prioritizes humanitarian access, regional stability, and the safety of civilians. While ASEAN has a non-interference policy, violence against civilians is a clear moral boundary.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7373034</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Japan’s Takaichi Wins Snap Election by Landslide: What You Need to Know</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7372956/japan-takaichi-election-win/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rebecca Schneid and Chad de Guzman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 08 Feb 2026 19:31:13 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7372956</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The conservative Prime Minister’s gamble seems to have paid off.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7372956"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7372956/japan-takaichi-election-win/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/GettyImages-2260006598.jpg" alt="Japan's Lower House Election Is Held"/>



<p>Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi made history once again after leading her party to a landslide victory in a general election on Sunday&mdash;a result that could significantly alter the country&rsquo;s relationship with China and lead to deep domestic economic reforms.&nbsp;</p>

[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]



<p>Takaichi&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7346495/japan-sanae-takaichi-snap-election-ldp/" >decision to hold a snap election</a> just months after her <a href="https://time.com/7327260/japan-prime-minister-sanae-takaichi-ldp-coalition-komeito-ishin-analysis/" >glass-breaking rise to power</a> paid off as her Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) secured 316 of the 465 seats in the parliament&rsquo;s lower house&mdash;enough to form a supermajority and a dramatic increase from the LDP and its coalition partner&rsquo;s joint 232 seats before the election.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;I wanted the voters to give me a mandate because I advocated for responsible, proactive fiscal policy that would significantly shift economic and fiscal policy,&rdquo; Takaichi <a href="https://news.web.nhk/newsweb/na/na-k10015046831000"  target="_blank">told public broadcaster NHK</a> late Sunday.</p>



<p>Takaichi, who just a few months ago became <a href="https://time.com/7323329/sanae-takaichi-japan-prime-minister/" >Japan&rsquo;s first female Prime Minister</a> after her predecessor Shigeru Ishiba <a href="https://time.com/7315284/shigeru-ishiba-japan-prime-minister-resignation-ldp-future-analysis-explainer/" >resigned</a> as head of the LDP amid waning support for the long-ruling party, has now presided over the LDP&rsquo;s biggest electoral victory since its 1955 founding, surpassing the previous record-holding 300 lower house seats won during former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone&rsquo;s Administration in 1986.</p>



<p>Even though Japan wasn&rsquo;t due for another general election until late 2028, Takaichi called the election in hopes of capitalizing on high public approval ratings during her early tenure to gain a mandate and the legislative strength to introduce her sweeping conservative agenda.</p>



<p>Experts tell TIME that the LDP&rsquo;s election success leaned heavily on Takaichi&rsquo;s brand of leadership. Standing out for her dynamism in a party previously dominated by older men, her pledge to &ldquo;work, work, work&rdquo; on behalf of the country, as well as a strong social media campaign, won over disillusioned young voters.</p>



<p>&ldquo;This was a very personal campaign,&rdquo; says Jeff Kingston, a professor of Asian studies and history at Temple University&rsquo;s Japan campus. &ldquo;It was all about Takaichi, and they looked at her, and they looked at the other potential leaders and found them wanting.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Takaichi campaigned on a tougher stance toward China, rebuilding Japan&#8217;s military, tougher immigration rules, and economic reforms. She also earned the &ldquo;<a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/116019257556623305"  target="_blank">complete and total endorsement</a>&rdquo; of U.S. President Donald Trump, with whom she has <a href="https://time.com/7328829/sanae-takaichi-donald-trump-japan-us-trade-defense-ishiba-abe/" >established a strong working relationship</a>.</p>



<p>Trump congratulated Takaichi on her &ldquo;LANDSLIDE Victory&rdquo; in a <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/116037545036564953"  target="_blank">post</a> on Truth Social on Sunday.</p>



<p>Here&#8217;s what you need to know about what comes next.&nbsp;</p>



<p>A loyal legislature</p>



<p>Kingston says the LDP&rsquo;s success, buttressed by an additional 36 seats won by its coalition partner Japan Innovation Party, effectively allows Takaichi to pursue whatever policies she wants. &ldquo;The opposition has been decimated,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s really no guardrails out there.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Jeffrey Hall, a lecturer at Kanda University of International Studies in Japan, adds that many of the LDP&rsquo;s new victors, including some who lost their seats in 2024, are now effectively Takaichi&rsquo;s &ldquo;children.&rdquo; They&rsquo;ll look to her&nbsp; &ldquo;for protection,&rdquo; he says, and they&rsquo;ll be expected to &ldquo;support their political mom.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Change in Japan-China relations</h2>



<p>Experts say that the LDP&rsquo;s resounding win signals an end for now to Japan&rsquo;s &ldquo;revolving-door&rdquo; politics. And with Takaichi presumed to have years remaining in power, China will have to navigate the increasingly tense relationship her early Administration has already exhibited.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Shortly after taking office, Takaichi made waves by publicly stating that Japan might respond to an invasion of Taiwan, noting that such an invasion could trigger collective self-defense and a &ldquo;survival-threatening situation.&rdquo; She has also said she would bolster Japan&rsquo;s military, further eroding decades of pacifist policy that began after World War II.</p>



<p>Takaichi&rsquo;s comments <a href="https://time.com/7334371/china-japan-taiwan-takaichi-explainer/" >provoked the ire of China</a>, which views Taiwan as part of its territory. Beijing has responded with attempts to isolate Japan, telling Chinese tourists to &ldquo;avoid traveling&rdquo; there in the near future and reimposing a ban on Japanese seafood imports.</p>



<p><strong>Read More: </strong><a href="https://time.com/7336391/china-japan-taiwan-dispute-takaichi-xi-economic-costs-diplomatic-relations/" ><em>How the China-Japan Rift Could Cost Both Countries</em></a></p>



<p>But domestically, while opponents have criticized her hawkishness, nationalists have cheered Takaichi&rsquo;s unwillingness to cower to China&rsquo;s pressure campaign.</p>



<p>&ldquo;China initially assumed she would be a short-lived leader, based on recent past,&rdquo; Kingston says. &ldquo;They ratcheted up the wolf-warrior diplomacy, denounced her, vilified her, and demanded she retract. And what they did is inadvertently boost her popularity among the Japanese, because people rallied behind her against the regional bully.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Taiwan&rsquo;s President Lai Ching-te, meanwhile, was among the first foreign leaders to congratulate Takaichi,<a href="https://x.com/ChingteLai/status/2020502553675669884"  target="_blank"> saying on X</a> that he looks forward to facing &ldquo;regional challenges together in the spirit of shared values and mutually beneficial cooperation, thereby promoting peace and prosperity in the Indo-Pacific region.&rdquo; And in his congratulatory post, Trump praised Takaichi&rsquo;s &ldquo;Peace Through Strength Agenda.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Economic reforms</strong></h2>



<p>Domestically, Takaichi, who counts former conservative U.K. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher as her political hero, has pledged drastic economic reforms.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Among them is a plan to suspend the 8% consumption tax on food to ease the burden of rising prices on households.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We will accelerate talks over a sales tax reduction,&rdquo; Takaichi told reporters in the aftermath of the election on Sunday.</p>



<p>Takaichi also promised partial tax deductions for babysitting expenses and corporate tax incentives for companies that offer in-house childcare&mdash;a sign that she may be warming to more family-friendly policies.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We will prioritise the sustainability of fiscal policy. We will ensure necessary investments. Public and private sectors must invest. We will build a strong and resilient economy,&rdquo; she said Sunday.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Constitutional amendment</strong></h2>



<p>Takaichi may try to use her sweeping political mandate to push through structural change. The LDP has long sought to revise Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution, which establishes Japan&rsquo;s pacifist approach to conflict and dispute resolution and prohibits the maintenance of air, ground, and maritime military forces.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Why can&rsquo;t we write the Self-Defense Forces into the Constitution?&rdquo; Takaichi said in a Feb. 2 speech. &ldquo;I want you to let us revise the Constitution to position them as an effective organization.&rdquo;</p>



<p>But while the party now has a supermajority in the lower house, it doesn&rsquo;t have the same in the upper house. And amending the constitution would be an uphill battle, requiring support from two-thirds of lawmakers in both chambers as well as a public referendum.</p>



<p>Stephen Nagy, a professor of international relations at the International Christian University in Tokyo and a visiting fellow with the Japan Institute for International Affairs, says that Takaichi &ldquo;might be misreading the mandate if she focuses on constitutional revision.&rdquo; He believes that many of the people who backed her did so with inflation, cost of living, affordability and wages top of mind.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Gender politics</strong></h2>



<p>Though Takaichi made history as the country&rsquo;s first female Prime Minister in October 2025, her stance on gender and sexuality politics has prompted mixed reactions to her rise.</p>



<p>Takaichi supports the imperial family&rsquo;s male-only succession and opposes same-sex marriage as well as amending the 19th-century law requiring married couples to have the same surname, under which most women are pressured into abandoning theirs. While there is growing support in Japan for couples to be able to have different surnames, Takaichi<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-55472446"  target="_blank"> said</a> the practice &ldquo;may destroy the social structure based on family units.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;She doesn&rsquo;t have a very positive track record on gender issues, on family-friendly policies, women&rsquo;s empowerment,&rdquo; Kingston <a href="https://time.com/7322887/japan-sanae-takaichi-ldp-leader-election-first-female-prime-minister/" >told TIME last year</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7372956</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Lindsey Vonn&#8217;s Olympic Crash, Through The Eyes Of Her Family</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7372933/lindsey-vonn-olympics-crash/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Sean Gregory / Cortina d'Ampezzo ]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 08 Feb 2026 16:04:51 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[2026 Milan and Cortina d'Ampezzo Olympics]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7372933</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The crowd fell silent as Vonn crashed during her attempt at the impossible. Her family watched on in horror. ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7372933"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7372933/lindsey-vonn-olympics-crash/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/AP26039404715882.jpg" alt="APTOPIX Milan Cortina Olympics Alpine Skiing"/>



<p>Karin and Laura Kildow, <a href="https://time.com/7328290/lindsey-vonn-olympics-comeback-interview/" >Lindsey Vonn&rsquo;s </a>younger sisters, held hands before their older sibling entered the starting gate at the Olympic women&rsquo;s downhill competition in Cortina d&rsquo;Ampezzo, Italy, on Sunday. Along with the rest of the world, they awaited to see if she could pull off the impossible: win an Olympic medal, maybe even a gold, at 41, following not only knee replacement surgery on her right knee, but a <a href="https://time.com/7366530/can-you-ski-with-a-torn-acl-lindsey-vonn/" >ruptured ACL </a>in her left one, which she suffered in a downhill crash a little more than a week ago. Repeat: a week ago. </p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>On<a href="https://time.com/7368808/super-bowl-2026-seahawks-patriots/" > Super Bowl Sunday,</a> this high-speed downhill&mdash;already the most prestigious race in all of skiing&mdash;had become a sort of Super Bowl stand-in at these Olympics. In the second row, Karin wore a black cowboy hat and a Team USA jacket. Laura wore a blue USA beanie. Karin&rsquo;s left hand clutched Laura&rsquo;s right one. Karin closed her eyes, and took a deep breath.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Their father, Alan Kildow, stood upright by their side. They all knew the risks of this Olympic run, of Vonn&rsquo;s determination to finish her comeback. Vonn took deep breaths too, and jumped out of the gate, but some 13 seconds into her race, her arm clipped a gate, and she spun and tumbled hard down the course. Karin screamed in horror, and bowed her head. Laura recoiled, and closed her eyes. Alan crossed his arms, stoic for the moment. Soon afterwards, he reached under the left lens of his sunglasses, seeming to wipe away a tear. He bit his bottom lip.&nbsp;</p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7328290/lindsey-vonn-olympics-comeback-interview/" ><em>Inside Lindsey Vonn&rsquo;s Unprecedented Attempt at an Olympic Comeback</em></a></p>



<p>The venue went eerily silent, except for the completely incongruous dance music playing over a loudspeaker. Couldn&rsquo;t someone make that stop? About a half-dozen emergency personnel attended to Vonn on the mountain. She appeared to clutch her left knee. She screamed. Some ten minutes later, a yellow helicopter flew over the mountain. Vonn was airlifted off the course. The crowd waved to Vonn as she was taken away.</p>



<p>On their way out of the venue, Karin and Laura stopped to take some pictures and exchange words with <a href="https://time.com/7277168/snoop-dogg-interview-time100-2025/" >Snoop Dogg</a>, who was in Cortina in his capacity as NBC roving correspondent. Snoop was wearing a Vonn shirt. Under the stands, Karin and Laura joined a few other people for a group hug. &ldquo;I will say that Snoop Dogg really picked me up,&rdquo; Laura told TIME moments later. &ldquo;He said, &lsquo;Stay strong for Lindsey.&rsquo; That&rsquo;s helping me right now. It looked really bad, but I&#8217;m glad that we&#8217;re all here.&rdquo; Karin cited <a href="https://www.worldfuturefund.org/Documents/maninarena.htm"  target="_blank">&ldquo;Man In The Arena,&rdquo; </a>the famous Teddy Roosevelt speech. &ldquo;The people who dare greatly are the ones that should be admired, and she dared greatly,&rdquo; Karin tells TIME through tears. &ldquo;She dared greatly. She put it all on the line.&rdquo; In a statement, U.S. Ski and Snowboard said Vonn had &#8220;sustained an injury, but is in stable condition and in good hands with a team of American and Italian physicians.&#8221;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/AP26039459022292.jpg" alt="Milan Cortina Olympics Alpine Skiing" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>For Vonn&rsquo;s immediate family&mdash;her mother, Linda Anne Krohn, died of ALS in 2022&mdash;the clear, beautiful morning in Italy&rsquo;s Dolomites mountain range started out with so much hope. Vonn loved racing in Cortina, and the prospect of finishing her Olympic career in this beloved location was an impetus for her comeback. Before Vonn&rsquo;s Olympic race, Karin told TIME she had been sick to her stomach the previous few days. Her worry made her cry.&nbsp; But she was calm now.&nbsp;</p>



<p>After Vonn injured her knee at the final World Cup downhill before the Olympics, Karin had reminded her older sister that she did not <em>have</em> to compete in the Games. After all, her outstanding results on the World Cup circuit this season&mdash;two race wins, four more podiums&mdash;already certified her status as an all-time great athlete. Only a fool would question a decision to skip the Games to preserve her health.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;She said, &lsquo;Never, ever say that to me again,&rsquo;&rdquo; says Karin.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Alan did his yoga and meditation the morning of the race, and wanted to make a point in a pre-race conversation with TIME. He lives in Vail, Colo., and many older people have been coming up to him in recent weeks, telling him that Vonn&rsquo;s comeback has inspired them on their own quests for athletic longevity, even if only on a recreational level. What she was doing transcended skiing.</p>



<p>Lindsey texted her father that morning, telling him she&rsquo;s got this.&nbsp;</p>



<p>After the crash, as Alan was about to make his own exit, he was asked if he wanted to share any thoughts. Maybe later, he said. First, he wanted to check up on his daughter.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;I think she&rsquo;s pretty badly hurt.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
