		<item>
		<title>Trump Shares Message From France’s Macron Questioning Greenland Moves</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7353344/greenland-france-macron-trump-diplomacy-denmark/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Miranda Jeyaretnam]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 20 Jan 2026 09:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7353344</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[“I do not understand what you are doing on Greenland,” the French President said, according to the screenshot.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7353344"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7353344/greenland-france-macron-trump-diplomacy-denmark/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/greenland-trump.jpg" alt="Smartphone Displays Donald Trump Post on Truth Social About Greenland"/>



<p>President Donald Trump shared what appeared to be a message from French President Emmanuel Macron questioning his moves on Greenland amid the Trump Administration&rsquo;s renewed push to take control of the territory.</p>



<p>&ldquo;My friend, We are totally in line on Syria. We can do great things on Iran,&rdquo; read the message, which was attached as a screenshot to Trump&rsquo;s Truth Social <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115925848634299232"  target="_blank">post</a> late Monday night, early Tuesday. &ldquo;I do not understand what you are doing on Greenland.&rdquo;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Macron also offered to host a G7 meeting in Paris after the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, this week.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Let us try to build great things : 1) i can set up a g7 meeting after Davos in Paris on thursday afternoon. I can invite the ukrainians, the danish, the syrians and the russians in the margins 2) let us have a dinner together in Paris together on thursday before you go back to the us,&rdquo; the message read.</p>



<p>Trump did not include a reason for sharing the message, captioning the post only with &ldquo;Note from President Emmanuel Macron, of France.&rdquo; TIME has reached out to the White House and Macron&rsquo;s official residence, the &Eacute;lys&eacute;e Palace, for comment. <a href="https://www.barrons.com/news/macron-sent-message-to-trump-offering-to-host-g7-meeting-in-paris-thursday-entourage-f4a1cc9c"  target="_blank">AFP</a> reported that the French President&rsquo;s entourage confirmed the authenticity of the message.</p>



<p>Trump also <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115926107400617491"  target="_blank">shared</a> a message from NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte after a phone call concerning Greenland assuring Trump that he is &ldquo;committed to finding a way forward on Greenland.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;As I expressed to everyone, very plainly, Greenland is imperative for National and World Security,&rdquo; Trump <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115925766187001811"  target="_blank">said</a> in a post early Tuesday, adding that he would be meeting with &ldquo;various parties&rdquo; about Greenland in Davos. &ldquo;There can be no going back &mdash; On that, everyone agrees!&rdquo;</p>



<p>Since the <a href="https://time.com/7344628/us-venezuela-trump-maduro-oil-drugs-war-explainer-questions-answered/" >U.S.&rsquo;s military intervention in Venezuela</a> and capture of its leader Nicol&aacute;s Maduro at the start of the year, Trump has <a href="https://time.com/7344147/greenland-denmark-trump-takeover-independence-purchase-military-nato/" >ramped up his effort to wrest control of Greenland</a>, which is a part of the <a href="https://time.com/7347183/denmark-greenland-trump-europe/" >Kingdom of Denmark</a>. Both the E.U. and Greenland have <a href="https://time.com/7345949/greenland-denmark-trump/" >objected</a> to Trump&rsquo;s claims over the territory, and the dispute threatens to unravel the NATO defense alliance and upend the U.S.&rsquo;s relationship with its allies.</p>



<p>Over the weekend, Trump <a href="https://time.com/7352424/republicans-denounce-trump-greenland-tariffs-threat-america-risk/" >threatened</a> to impose a 10% tariff on European allies from Feb. 1, which would increase to 25% in June, unless Denmark agrees to sell Greenland to the U.S. He also suggested that the use of force was <a href="https://time.com/7347751/trump-letter-norway-store-nobel-peace-prize-obligation-greenland-war/" >not off the table</a> in a letter sent to Norway&rsquo;s leader Jonas Gahr St&oslash;re.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Considering your Country decided not to give me the Nobel Peace Prize for having stopped 8 Wars PLUS, I no longer feel an obligation to think purely of Peace,&rdquo; Trump said in the letter.</p>



<p>Trump has also sparred with Macron in recent days. While the E.U. <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-01-19/eu-eyes-tariffs-on-93-billion-of-us-goods-over-new-trump-threat"  target="_blank">weighs</a> potential retaliatory tariffs of &euro;93 billion ($108 billion) on U.S. goods among other countermeasures, Macron has called Trump&rsquo;s tariff threat over Greenland &ldquo;unacceptable&rdquo; and <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-01-18/macron-to-seek-use-of-eu-anti-coercion-instrument-against-trump"  target="_blank">pushed</a> for the E.U. to use its anti-coercion instrument for the first time, which could restrict U.S. participation in the E.U. market. Trump also floated the possibility of imposing 200% tariffs on French wine and champagne after Macron declined to join Trump&rsquo;s &ldquo;Board of Peace&rdquo; over concerns that the board&rsquo;s charter goes beyond the U.N. mandate allowing it to oversee the reconstruction of Gaza through 2027.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Nobody wants him because he&rsquo;s going to be out of office very soon,&rdquo; Trump told reporters on Monday after his invitation was rebuffed.</p>



<p>Among a number of overnight posts on his social media platform, Trump also shared two apparently AI-generated or edited images depicting a U.S. takeover of Greenland. One <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/115925888562624963"  target="_blank">showed</a> a photo of him in the Oval Office talking to European leaders back in August with a fake map of Greenland overlaid with the U.S. flag in the background. (Canada and Venezuela were also overlaid with the U.S. flag.) The other <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/115925897257210763"  target="_blank">showed</a> him, flanked by Secretary of State Marco Rubio and Vice President J.D. Vance, planting the U.S. flag in Greenland soil.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7353344</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Starmer Breaks With Trump Over &#8216;Completely Wrong&#8217; Greenland Tariff Threats and Urges Avoiding a Trade War</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7349367/trump-greenland-tariff-threats-europe-fallout-starmer/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Olivia-Anne Cleary]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Jan 2026 12:15:52 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7349367</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Trump threatened to impose a 25% tariff on European allies until Denmark sells Greenland to the U.S.—a move Starmer has labeled “completely wrong.”]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7349367"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7349367/trump-greenland-tariff-threats-europe-fallout-starmer/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2201636112.jpg" alt="UK Prime Minister Meets With President Trump In Washington"/>



<p>British Prime Minister Keir Starmer has publicly broken ranks with U.S. President Donald Trump over his renewed pressure campaign for the <a href="https://time.com/7344316/republicans-break-ranks-with-trump-over-greenland-annexation-threat/" >annexation of Greenland</a>. Trump threatened to impose a 25% tariff on the U.K. and other European allies until Denmark relents and sells the territory of Greenland&mdash;a move <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-remarks-on-greenland-19-january-2026"  target="_blank">Starmer has labeled &ldquo;completely wrong.&rdquo;</a></p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>During a press conference at Downing Street on Monday morning, Starmer argued the use of tariffs against allies &ldquo;is not the right way to resolve differences within an alliance, nor is it helpful to frame efforts to strengthen Greenland&rsquo;s security as a justification for economic pressure.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Referring to the matter as a &ldquo;very serious situation,&rdquo; Starmer&mdash;who rejected the idea of retaliatory tariffs against the U.S., for now at least&mdash;said a &ldquo;trade war is in no one&rsquo;s interest&rdquo; and emphasized that his priority is to act in the national interest of the United Kingdom.</p>



<p>&ldquo;On Greenland, the right way to approach an issue of this seriousness is through calm discussion between allies. Let&rsquo;s be clear, the security of Greenland matters and it will matter more as climate change reshapes the Arctic,&rdquo; said Starmer. &ldquo;As sea routes open and strategic competition intensifies, the High North will require greater attention, greater investment, and stronger collective defence.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The U.K. is ready to assist NATO allies on that front, Starmer vowed, before stating that no plan can be made without the involvement of Greenland and Denmark.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Any decision about the future status of Greenland belongs to the people of Greenland and the Kingdom of Denmark alone. That right is fundamental, and we will support it,&rdquo; Starmer said, taking a clear stance against Trump&rsquo;s rhetoric, which includes the White House refusing to rule out taking Greenland by military force.</p>



<p>Greenland and Denmark have repeatedly denounced Trump&#8217;s attempts to annex the island. In his strongest pushback yet, Greenlandic Prime Minister Jens-Frederik Nielsen plainly stated last week &ldquo;if we have to choose between the United States and Denmark here and now, we choose Denmark.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read More</strong>: <em><a href="https://time.com/7346819/can-trump-pull-united-states-out-of-nato-legal-experts/" >Trump Refuses to Rule Out Leaving NATO Over Greenland Tussle&mdash;Can He Legally Do That?</a></em></p>



<p>Starmer&rsquo;s public rebuke of Trump&rsquo;s tariffs threat stands in stark contrast to the strong working relationship he has cultivated with the U.S. President over the past year. The two previously put on a united front for a &ldquo;groundbreaking&rdquo; <a href="https://time.com/7318214/trump-starmer-us-uk-tech-prosperity-deal-signed/" >billion-dollar U.K.-U.S. Tech Prosperity Deal</a> and were the first leaders to agree on a reciprocal <a href="https://time.com/7283842/united-states-united-kingdom-trade-deal-trump-starmer-tariffs-agreement/" >trade agreement amid Trump&rsquo;s initial &ldquo;Liberation Day&rdquo; tariffs push.</a> More recently, the <a href="https://time.com/7344656/united-kingdom-helped-united-states-trump-seize-oil-tankers/" >U.K. helped the U.S. seize</a> a Russian-flagged tanker in the North Atlantic.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2236082748.jpg" alt="UK Hosts President Trump And First Lady Melania Trump For State Visit - Day Three" alignment="original-size-image"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>Highlighting his wish for the strong alliance to continue, Starmer told reporters at Downing Street that the relationship between the U.K. and the U.S. &ldquo;matters profoundly, not just to our security, but to the prosperity and stability that people here depend upon.&rdquo; He said he&rsquo;s determined to keep that relationship &ldquo;strong, constructive, and focused on results.&rdquo;</p>



<p>However, although a calm approach to the matter is preferred, in a show of strength at home, Starmer, who shared his disapproval personally with Trump during a phone call on Sunday, emphasized that &ldquo;being pragmatic does not mean being passive.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump on Saturday <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115911344443637897"  target="_blank">said he would impose</a> a 10% tariff on Denmark, Norway, Sweden, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Finland, and the United Kingdom beginning Feb. 1 &ldquo;on any and all goods sent to the United States of America.&rdquo; He said the tariff would be increased to 25% on June 1.</p>



<p>NATO chief Mark Rutte last week expressed the importance of &ldquo;the Arctic and Arctic security,&#8221; and several European NATO allies committed to sending military personnel to Greenland to strengthen that security amid heightened concerns over the territory. Trump appeared to reference this in his tariffs threat, citing that European nations &ldquo;have journeyed to Greenland, for purposes unknown.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read More:</strong> <em><a href="https://time.com/7344316/republicans-break-ranks-with-trump-over-greenland-annexation-threat/" >The Republicans Breaking Ranks With Trump Over Greenland Threats: &lsquo;This Is Appalling&rsquo;</a></em></p>



<p>The eight countries threatened with the charges put on a united front over the weekend via a joint statement issued in response to Trump.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Tariff threats undermine transatlantic relations and risk a dangerous downward spiral. We will continue to stand united and coordinated in our response. We are committed to upholding our sovereignty,&rdquo; <a href="https://www.government.se/statements/2026/01/statement-by-denmark-finland-france-germany-the-netherlands-norway-sweden-and-the-united-kingdom/"  target="_blank">the statement read.</a></p>



<p>However, Starmer&rsquo;s approach to Trump&rsquo;s threat&mdash;and his disinterest in retaliatory tariffs&mdash;may well differ from that of the E.U. leaders who are set to discuss ways forward during an emergency summit in Brussels on Thursday, <a href="https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2026/01/18/statement-by-president-costa-on-greenland/"  target="_blank">as arranged by president of the European Council</a> Ant&oacute;nio Costa.</p>



<p>On Monday, German Finance Minister Lars Klingbeil and his French counterpart, Roland Lescure, weighed up various countermeasures at the disposal of the E.U., with Klingbeil asserting: &ldquo;We will not allow ourselves to be blackmailed.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read More</strong> <em><a href="https://time.com/7346104/trump-greenland-annexation-threat-us-control/" >Trump Declares Anything Less Than U.S. Control of Greenland Is &lsquo;Unacceptable&rsquo;</a></em></p>



<p>European tariffs on imports from the United States, a package of  93 billion euros ($107.7 billion) which is currently suspended until early February, could be enforced. Another option comes in the form of the Anti-Coercion Instrument (ACI), which could restrict access to the single market in which the U.S. has a surplus with the bloc and block applications for E.U. contracts. Lescure noted that this avenue should serve as more of a deterrent, with deescalation seemingly remaining the ultimate shared goal among E.U. leadership.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2256145614.jpg" alt="Greenland And Europe Hope To Avert U.S. Intervention To Acquire Greenland" alignment="original-size-image"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>Trump, meanwhile, has refused to rule out leaving NATO over the Greenland tussle, and maintains that anything less than <a href="https://time.com/7346104/trump-greenland-annexation-threat-us-control/" >U.S. control of Greenland is &ldquo;unacceptable.&rdquo;</a> According to the President, NATO &ldquo;should be leading the way for [the U.S.] to get it.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Greenland&#8217;s positioning between the U.S., Russia, and Europe makes it a strong geopolitical asset. Arguing that the U.S. acquiring Greenland is a &ldquo;national security&rdquo; matter, Trump has claimed that Denmark cannot be relied upon to protect Greenland from Russian and Chinese interests. </p>



<p>Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov on Monday declined to comment when asked about the perceived Russian threat against Greenland but, according to Reuters, he told reporters that Trump would go down in &ldquo;world history&rdquo; if the U.S. were to acquire the territory.<br><br></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7349367</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Trump Sets Price Tag for Peace Board Membership</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347276/board-of-peace-gaza-un-trump-billion-dollar-membership-fee/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chad de Guzman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Jan 2026 09:45:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347276</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[According to a draft charter, $1 billion can buy a permanent seat on what some speculate Trump is building to be a U.S.-led rival to the United Nations.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347276"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347276/board-of-peace-gaza-un-trump-billion-dollar-membership-fee/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/donald-trump_71c177.jpg" alt="U.S. President Donald Trump stands in the ballroom at Mar-a-Lago in Palm Beach, Fla., on Jan. 16, 2026."/>



<p>Donald Trump has <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115901692370933354"  target="_blank">described</a> his proposed &ldquo;Board of Peace&rdquo;&mdash;the body that will oversee the transition and reconstruction of the war-wrought Gaza Strip&mdash;as &ldquo;the Greatest and Most Prestigious Board ever assembled at any time, any place.&rdquo; But that prestige apparently comes with a hefty price tag.</p>



[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]

<p>Countries will have to cough up at least $1 billion in order to secure a permanent seat on the board, according to a draft charter, while other members will have three-year terms. <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-01-17/trump-wants-nations-to-pay-1-billion-to-stay-on-his-peace-board"  target="_blank">Bloomberg</a> first reported on the high fee, and <a href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/full-text-charter-of-trumps-board-of-peace/"  target="_blank"><em>The</em> <em>Times of Israel</em></a> posted a copy of the draft charter text.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Each Member State shall serve a term of no more than three years from this Charter&rsquo;s entry into force, subject to renewal by the Chairman. The three-year membership term shall not apply to Member States that contribute more than USD $1,000,000,000 in cash funds to the Board of Peace within the first year of the Charter&rsquo;s entry into force,&rdquo; the draft reportedly says.</p>



<p>It&rsquo;s unclear how exactly the contribution will be used. The <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2026/01/18/trump-peace-board/"  target="_blank"><em>Washington Post</em></a> reported, citing an unnamed senior European official, that European leaders are in talks over Trump&rsquo;s ambitions for the board, which appear to be more expansive than just settling the Gaza conflict. The official also reportedly said that despite Europe&rsquo;s commitments to the Strip, there&rsquo;s little appetite to significantly fund an organization that advances a Trump-led world order, amid speculation that the Board of Peace is being devised as an <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/0ee79faa-86d3-4c01-a180-add6e164ac28"  target="_blank">alternative to the United Nations</a>, which the U.S. under Trump has increasingly been hostile to.</p>



<p>Bloomberg added, citing unnamed sources, that most countries that could have joined the board have found it unacceptable that the draft appears to suggest Trump&mdash;who would be the board&rsquo;s inaugural chair&mdash;would manage its funds.</p>



<p>In dispelling claims about the fee, the White House&rsquo;s <a href="https://x.com/RapidResponse47/status/2012684845109874988"  target="_blank">rapid response account</a> on X said the fee &#8220;simply offers permanent membership to partner countries who demonstrate deep commitment to peace, security, and prosperity.&#8221; An unnamed U.S. official also told Bloomberg that all money the board raises will be used to accomplish its mandate to rebuild Gaza.</p>



<p>Invitations to join Trump&rsquo;s board were sent out to several countries over the weekend, including <a href="https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-invited-to-sit-on-trumps-board-of-peace-for-gaza/article70523013.ece"  target="_blank">India</a>, <a href="https://x.com/ForeignMinistry/status/2012801567519330610?s=20"  target="_blank">Jordan</a>, <a href="https://www.iletisim.gov.tr/english/haberler/detay/head-of-communications-durans-statement-on-president-erdogans-invitation-to-un-board-of-peace"  target="_blank">T&uuml;rkiye</a>, and <a href="https://www.barrons.com/news/trump-invites-sisi-to-join-gaza-board-of-peace-egypt-fm-3fd68d57?gaa_at=eafs&amp;gaa_n=AWEtsqcV--1D_CbDF0mczAye928IFkWijOTpSX2-QyE5tox3RbrGOZbnC_2uOweoEmM%3D&amp;gaa_ts=696dae9b&amp;gaa_sig=HmMn1pMiDSKqACz0FvvxHUPSaRj0a3dOV5xY1lSd5jefy5g35AF6lkKy1_A6-J2xNzjZ8r69PS5x0-hilyvmuQ%3D%3D"  target="_blank">Egypt</a>. Some of them, particularly those allied with Trump, swiftly accepted the invite: <a href="https://x.com/JMilei/status/2012495664546992638"  target="_blank">Argentina</a> President Javier Milei said it was an &ldquo;honor&rdquo; to be invited as he posted Trump&rsquo;s invitation letter on social media, as did <a href="https://www.instagram.com/orbanviktor/p/DTpcGzRjfPx/?hl=en"  target="_blank">Hungary&rsquo;s Viktor Orb&aacute;n</a>.</p>



<p>Others, however, were more circumspect with the invitation. British paper <a href="https://www.thetimes.com/world/middle-east/israel-hamas-war/article/trump-gaza-peace-board-members-lc5zv5fsp?utm_source=chatgpt.com"  target="_blank"><em>The Times of London</em></a> reported that U.K. ministers are concerned about where funds would go and what legal framework the board is using to operate. Canada&rsquo;s Prime Minister Mark Carney <a href="https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-trump-gaza-board-of-peace-carney-palestine-israel-hamas/"  target="_blank">told reporters Sunday</a> that Trump had approached him about the board weeks back but said that &ldquo;with respect to the specifics of the &lsquo;Board of Peace&rsquo;, we haven&rsquo;t gone through all the details of the structure, how it&rsquo;s going to work, what financing is for, etc. &hellip; And so we will work through those in the coming days.&rdquo;</p>



<p>On Friday, the White House <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/2026/01/statement-on-president-trumps-comprehensive-plan-to-end-the-gaza-conflict/"  target="_blank">announced</a> the board&rsquo;s founding members, including Secretary of State Marco Rubio, U.S. special envoy for peace missions Steve Witkoff, Trump&rsquo;s son-in-law Jared Kushner, former U.K. Prime Minister Tony Blair, and World Bank Group president Ajay Banga. A spokesperson for Blair <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-01-18/blair-distances-himself-from-trump-s-1-billion-peace-board-fee"  target="_blank">told Bloomberg</a> that he wasn&rsquo;t involved in determining board membership and that questions about the high fee should be directed to the Trump Administration.</p>



<p>The Trump Administration <a href="https://x.com/RapidResponse47/status/1972726021196562494"  target="_blank">has also said</a> that the board &#8220;will set the framework and handle the funding for the redevelopment of Gaza,&rdquo; but a review of the draft charter text makes no explicit mention of Gaza. The draft charter describes the board as &ldquo;an international organization that seeks to promote stability, restore dependable and lawful governance, and secure enduring peace in areas affected or threatened by conflict.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The U.N. Security Council in November <a href="https://docs.un.org/en/s/res/2803(2025)"  target="_blank">adopted a resolution</a> backing Trump&rsquo;s proposed board to set the framework and coordinate funding for Gaza&rsquo;s redevelopment, though it only authorized the board&rsquo;s mandate until 2027.</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s plans for the Board of Peace also come as he has threatened to <a href="https://time.com/7344877/trump-greenland-annexation-threats-purchase-national-security-economic/" >take over Greenland</a>, <a href="https://time.com/7347751/trump-letter-norway-store-nobel-peace-prize-obligation-greenland-war/" >warning late Sunday in a reported letter to Norway</a>&mdash;one of several countries the U.S. <a href="https://time.com/7347149/greenland-tariffs/" >sanctioned with tariffs</a> over a show of support to Greenland&mdash;that after <a href="https://time.com/7324832/trump-loses-nobel-peace-prize-maria-corina-machado/" >not receiving last year&rsquo;s Nobel Prize</a>, he &ldquo;no longer feel[s] an obligation to think purely of Peace.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347276</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Trump Says No Need ‘To Think Purely of Peace’ in Letter to Norway About Nobel Prize Loss, Greenland Ambitions</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347751/trump-letter-norway-store-nobel-peace-prize-obligation-greenland-war/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chad de Guzman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Jan 2026 09:45:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347751</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Trump suggested in a letter to Norway’s leader that losing the Nobel Peace Prize opened up his options for taking Greenland.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347751"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347751/trump-letter-norway-store-nobel-peace-prize-obligation-greenland-war/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/donald-trump_28d7eb.jpg" alt="President Donald Trump speaks to reporters at the White House in Washington, D.C. on Jan. 16, 2026. "/>



<p>Donald Trump sent an ominous warning to the Prime Minister of Norway, suggesting that war could be on the table in his <a href="https://time.com/7344877/trump-greenland-annexation-threats-purchase-national-security-economic/" >pursuit of Greenland</a>, an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of <a href="https://time.com/7347183/denmark-greenland-trump-europe/" >Denmark</a>.</p>



<p>In a <a href="https://x.com/nickschifrin/status/2013107018081489006"  target="_blank">letter shared late Sunday by PBS journalist Nick Schifrin</a> from the U.S. President to Norway&rsquo;s leader Jonas Gahr St&oslash;re, Trump warned that after not winning last year&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7324832/trump-loses-nobel-peace-prize-maria-corina-machado/" >Nobel Peace Prize</a> &ldquo;for having stopped 8 Wars PLUS,&rdquo; he &ldquo;no longer feel[s] an obligation to think purely of Peace, although it will always be predominant, but can now think about what is good and proper for the United States of America.&rdquo; </p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Trump has in the past <a href="https://trumpstruth.org/statuses/34476"  target="_blank">conflated the honor</a>, which is given by the Norway-based Nobel Committee, with the nation and its government. Of his denial of the Peace Prize, Trump told Fox News&rsquo; Sean Hannity earlier this month: &ldquo;It&#8217;s been a very big embarrassment to the country of Norway. Whether they have anything to do with it or not. I think they do. They say they don&rsquo;t.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read More: </strong><a href="https://time.com/7339536/trump-peace-deals-conflicts-status-thailand-cambodia/" ><em>In Places Trump Has Touted Bringing Peace, Conflict Still Rages</em></a></p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s letter to St&oslash;re went on to tie his warning of no longer thinking &ldquo;purely of peace&rdquo; to his campaign to take over Greenland.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Denmark cannot protect that land from Russia or China, and why do they have a &lsquo;right of ownership&rsquo; anyway?&rdquo; he continued. &ldquo;There are no written documents, it&rsquo;s only that a boat landed there hundreds of years ago, but we had boats landing there, also. I have done more for NATO than any other person since its founding, and now, NATO should do something for the United States. The World is not secure unless we have Complete and Total Control of Greenland.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The National Security Council also reportedly forwarded the letter to European ambassadors in Washington, according to Schifrin&rsquo;s X post.</p>



<p>St&oslash;re confirmed to <a href="https://www.vg.no/nyheter/i/q6AdB0/trump-i-melding-til-stoere-foeler-ikke-lenger-noen-forpliktelse"  target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Norwegian news outlet VG</a> that he received the letter, saying that Trump&rsquo;s note was a response to an earlier message where he and Finland&#8217;s President Alexander Stubb sought a conversation with their U.S. counterpart.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The President is committed to establishing long-term peace at home and abroad,&rdquo; White House spokesperson Anna Kelly said in a statement to TIME, when asked about the letter. &ldquo;President Trump believes Greenland is a strategically important location that is critical from the standpoint of national security, and he is confident Greenlanders would be better served if protected by the United States from modern threats in the Arctic region.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s message to St&oslash;re comes as he escalated pressure on fellow member-states in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) defense alliance to deliver Greenland to him. On Saturday, Trump announced on Truth Social that starting Feb. 1, he&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7347120/greenland-trump-protests-tariffs/" >imposing a 10% tariff</a> on a handful of NATO members, including Norway and Denmark, for <a href="https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/" >sending troops to Greenland</a>. That tariff will remain&mdash;and even increase to 25% come June&mdash;&ldquo;until such time as a Deal is reached for the Complete and Total purchase of Greenland,&rdquo; he said.</p>



<p><strong>Read More: </strong><a href="https://time.com/7347149/greenland-tariffs/" ><em>Europe Promises United Response to Trump&rsquo;s &lsquo;Dangerous&rsquo; Greenland Tariffs</em></a></p>



<p>NATO countries have fiercely opposed Trump&rsquo;s plan to occupy Greenland, and have criticized the U.S. President&rsquo;s attempts to pressure its allies with tariffs, which leaders from <a href="https://ga.de/vizekanzler-wir-duerfen-uns-nicht-erpressen-lassen_aid-142489597"  target="_blank">Germany</a>, the <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/china/dutch-minister-calls-trumps-greenland-tariff-threat-blackmail-2026-01-18/"  target="_blank">Netherlands</a>, and <a href="https://x.com/SwedishPM/status/2012589849585344518"  target="_blank">Sweden</a> have described as &ldquo;blackmail,&rdquo; to hand over the Danish territory.</p>



<p>Following the threat, European leaders, including French President Emmanuel Macron, have <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-01-18/macron-to-seek-use-of-eu-anti-coercion-instrument-against-trump"  target="_blank">reportedly</a> considered using the European Union&rsquo;s anti-coercion instrument&mdash;the bloc&rsquo;s retaliatory trade tool nicknamed the trade &ldquo;bazooka&rdquo; for how it could upend trans-Atlantic trade. The &ldquo;bazooka&rdquo; has never been used before on any country, but should the E.U. choose to, it could severely limit U.S. access to E.U. trade markets, through either tariffs or other import control measures.</p>



<p><a href="https://time.com/7346324/greenland-trump-polls-annexation-denmark/" >Most Americans</a> and <a href="https://time.com/7344316/republicans-break-ranks-with-trump-over-greenland-annexation-threat/" >even some Republicans</a> are not in support of Trump&rsquo;s plan to take Greenland, especially <a href="https://time.com/7344147/greenland-denmark-trump-takeover-independence-purchase-military-nato/" >if it involves force</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347751</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Inside the Danish Campaign to Keep Greenland, and Placate Trump</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347183/denmark-greenland-trump-europe/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lisa Abend]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 18 Jan 2026 19:24:10 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347183</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The Danes have tried everything to pacify the notoriously unpredictable president. Now they may be reaching their red line. ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347183"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347183/denmark-greenland-trump-europe/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2256362023.jpg" alt="GREENLAND-DENMARK-US-DEFENCE-NATO"/>



<p>President Donald Trump has often joked that Denmark&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7346104/trump-greenland-annexation-threat-us-control/" >defense of Greenland</a> is so paltry that it consists entirely of &ldquo;two dog sleds.&rdquo; As one of the few people to have manned those sleds, Kasper Dams&oslash; bristles at the remark.  </p>



<p>For two years in the late 1990s, the Danish elite special forces soldier patrolled the vast, frozen expanses of Greenland&rsquo;s uninhabited northeastern corner, often with only eleven dogs and one fellow soldier for company. His Sirius Patrol unit underwent the kind of hardcore physical training Navy SEALs receive, endured mental resilience training from NASA, and spent long months in minus-50-degree temperatures monitoring for any suspicious activity. So, although he acknowledges that Denmark needs to <a href="https://time.com/7347120/greenland-trump-protests-tariffs/" >increase its security investment</a> in Greenland, Dams&oslash; says the patrols are no joke. </p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>&ldquo;He can make fun of the dog sleds all he wants. But he should come and see what we do. Because then, no one will be laughing.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read more:</strong> <a href="https://time.com/7344877/trump-greenland-annexation-threats-purchase-national-security-economic/" ><em>Why Is Trump So Intent on Acquiring Greenland?</em></a></p>



<p>If Dams&oslash;&rsquo;s words suggest a bit of steel beneath the Danes&rsquo; normally agreeable exterior, it is a sentiment increasingly shared at the highest levels of government. As President Trump&rsquo;s long-standing desire to take over Greenland, a semi-autonomous territory within the kingdom of Denmark, has erupted into a full-blown crisis, the Danish government has been working fervently to prove itself a good ally and reach a diplomatic solution. But as Trump has continued to insist that Greenland must be taken, Denmark is also beginning to communicate, ever so delicately, that there are limits to its flexibility. And now that Trump has responded with further threats to its efforts to give him more of the Arctic security he says he wants, the pushback is spreading throughout Europe.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We have to work closer with our most reliable allies,&rdquo; said Rasmus Jarlov, chairman of the Danish parliament&rsquo;s defense committee, in an interview with TIME on Friday.&nbsp; &ldquo;And the ones that threaten us and alienate us, we will work a bit less with in the future. Maybe a lot less, depending on how this develops.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Although he initially expressed his desire to acquire Greenland for the United States during his first term, President Trump&rsquo;s Jan. 9 comments that he would take the island, which has a population of 57,000, &ldquo;the easy way&rdquo; or &ldquo;the hard way,&rdquo; came as a profound shock to both Danes and Greenlanders. The surprise stemmed not only from the belligerence of a message directed toward one of the U.S.&rsquo;s oldest and closest allies, but for its superfluousness.&nbsp; Greenland&rsquo;s leaders have made it clear they would welcome U.S. business investment, while Denmark already has treaties in place that allow the U.S. to expand its military presence.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;I&#8217;m still trying to grasp what it is the president really wants,&rdquo; said Stig &Oslash;stergaard Nielsen, a former commander of Denmark&rsquo;s Arctic Command, who is today a senior military advisor with the Copenhagen-based consultancy Rud Pedersen. &ldquo;The President has been told again and again that the treaties and agreements we already have with the United States allow them to have all the services and bases they can think of.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The Danish foreign minister, Lars L&oslash;kke Rasmussen, and his Greenlandic counterpart, Vivian Motzfeldt, sought to reinforce that point when they traveled to Washington this week to meet with Vice-President J.D. Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio. Although they left the meeting satisfied that both sides had agreed to a series of working meetings to negotiate options for greater security in the region while respecting what Rasmussen called the &ldquo;red lines&rdquo; of Denmark&rsquo;s sovereignty and Greenland&rsquo;s self-determination, the White House instead said that the meetings would deal with the U.S.&ldquo;acquisition of Greenland.&rdquo; &ldquo;In that case,&rdquo; Rasmussen muttered to the press, &#8220;it&rsquo;s going to be a short series.&rdquo;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2256745286.jpg" alt="Protest In Copenhagen Against US Threats To Annex Greenland" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>At the same time, Denmark has been busily bolstering its military presence in Greenland. A year ago, the government allocated $13.7 billion for investment in Arctic security, commissioning more drones, radar systems, and icebreaker ships, as well as an additional $37 million to increase the capacities of the Sirius Patrol, who, with their dogsleds, monitor otherwise inaccessible land. And this week, it sent more troops to Greenland, whose purpose, according to Defense Minister Troels Lund Poulsen, was &ldquo;to establish a more permanent military presence with a larger Danish contribution.&rdquo; </p>



<p>They&rsquo;re not doing it alone. Although previous Danish attempts to convince NATO to focus on the Arctic with initiatives like it those it is currently running in the Baltics have failed, this time many of its European allies, including France, Sweden, the UK, Norway, and the Netherlands, sent small numbers of troops to join an exercise intended to investigate the logistical and tactical needs for a more permanent presence. </p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/" ><em>Denmark Beefs Up Military Presence in Greenland </em></a></p>



<p>Yet, however eager the demonstrations of Denmark&rsquo;s contribution and NATO&rsquo;s collective goodwill may be, a more cold-eyed rationale may lie beneath their surface. &ldquo;The overt message is, let&#8217;s stand together. Let&#8217;s invest in NATO to protect this NATO territory,&rdquo; says Sten Rynning, professor of war studies at the University of Southern Denmark. &ldquo;And then there&rsquo;s a hidden message, which is that the Allies will not accept violations of sovereignty within the alliance.&rdquo; The joint participation, he argues, raises the political costs to the U.S. of intervention. &ldquo;It says to the Trump administration: &lsquo;If you&rsquo;re considering a military operation, you will have to handcuff soldiers from a lot of your allies&rsquo; countries, and take them away.&rsquo; It&#8217;s not about deterrence, it&#8217;s about complicating the calculations.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Danish Prime Minister Mette Frederiksen has warned bluntly that a U.S. military invasion would be the end of NATO. And on the diplomatic front, that threat seems to be Denmark&rsquo;s strongest card, as it works to persuade Republicans, including the two who joined a bipartisan congressional delegation to Copenhagen this week, to take action against the President&rsquo;s designs on the island. </p>



<p>Kay Bailey Hutchison, the former Republican senator from Texas who was ambassador to NATO during the first Trump administration, believes that ultimately, diplomacy will prevail.&nbsp; &ldquo;Any malign influence is going to affect both North America and Europe,&rdquo; Hutchison said. &ldquo;Which is really what NATO was built to deter. So I think that with America&rsquo;s lead in NATO, the way forward is to work with Denmark and our NATO allies to secure Greenland, and that negotiation is going to be the way out.&rdquo;</p>



<p>As tensions mount, others are no longer so sure that negotiation alone is enough. Earlier in the week, Thomas Crosbie, professor of military operations at the Danish Defense Academy, warned that it was unclear how the White House would interpret those military exercises in Greenland.  &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a bit of a paradox in that sending more troops could be seen as simply responsive to their [the Americans&rsquo;] requests. Or it could be seen as escalatory, depending on how it&rsquo;s framed.&rdquo;</p>



<p>On Saturday, the world seemingly got its answer when President Trump announced<a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115911344443637897"  target="_blank"> on Truth Social</a> that he would impose a 10% tariff on goods from Denmark and the seven countries supporting them on Greenland until &ldquo;a deal is reached for the complete and total purchase of Greenland.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>The European parliament, which had been set to approve the tariff deal it had negotiated with the Trump administration on Wednesday, put the plan on indefinite hold.&#8221;I see no possibility for the European Parliament to give the green light to move forward with the tariff agreement, Karin Karlsboro, Swedish member of the&nbsp; European Parliament and trade coordinator for the Renew coalition, told Politico. &ldquo;Instead, the EU must prepare to respond to President Trump&rsquo;s tariff attacks, including those targeting Sweden.&rdquo;</p>



<p>And just as European officials have been whispering&mdash;and <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/hit-back-donald-trump-europe-mulls-unthinkable-options-greenland-threats-ramp-up-tensions/"  target="_blank">sometimes shouting</a>&mdash;about whether it may be necessary to fight back with the so-called &lsquo;bazooka&rsquo; of its Anti-Coercion Instrument, so too are the continent&rsquo;s security advisors quietly beginning to weigh more extreme options. &ldquo;Could it be losing access to intelligence, to bases, to overflight corridors? I have only heard rumors, so it&#8217;s hard to say,&rdquo; said Rynning. &ldquo;My sense is that Europeans are at the point where they&#8217;re saying it&#8217;s one thing for you to push us around and question how much we spend, or if we&rsquo;re dressed improperly, or not living up to your manly standard. It&#8217;s quite another thing to violate our sovereignty. And so, there&#8217;s a sense that a red line has come into play.&rdquo; </p>



<p>For former Sirius patroller Dams&oslash;, who also fought in Afghanistan alongside U.S. troops, the escalating situation is causing some cognitive dissonance.&nbsp; Although he sees the current joint exercise as &ldquo;another coalition of the friendly,&rdquo; he regrets that the American-led alliance that has been central in his own military career now hangs in the balance. &ldquo;We all joined wars together, whether it was Iraq, or Afghanistan,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp; &ldquo;It was always together with our allies.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347183</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>At Least 5,000 Killed in Iran Protests, Official Says, As Trump Calls for Change in Leadership</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347170/iran-death-toll-khamenei-trump/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rebecca Schneid]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 18 Jan 2026 16:34:30 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347170</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[A complete shutdown of communications has made finding an accurate count impossible. The number may still go higher.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347170"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7347170/iran-death-toll-khamenei-trump/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255778473.jpg" alt="TOPSHOT-IRAN-PROTEST-RIGHTS"/>



<p>At least 5,000 people were killed in the protests that gripped <a href="https://time.com/7345555/iran-protests-deaths-us-trump-israel/" >Iran this month</a>, according to an Iranian official, 500 of whom were security personnel.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The toll is the highest yet cited by a government source for the nationwide protests that shook Iran&rsquo;s establishment and brought the United States to the brink of intervention.&nbsp;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>The Iranian official, who was quoted by Reuters, blamed &#8220;Israel and armed groups abroad&#8221; for the high number of people killed, and said the government&rsquo;s official count was unlikely to go much higher.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Protests erupted in Tehran after the rial, Iran&rsquo;s currency, crashed on December 28. The demonstrations quickly snowballed into a broader <a href="https://time.com/7345623/iran-protests-reza-shah-pahlavi-ayatollah-1979/" >anti-government movement</a> calling for the fall of Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.  </p>



<p><strong>Read More: </strong><a href="https://time.com/7346661/trump-iran-military-strikes-diplomacy-sanctions/" ><em>For Trump, a Path Forward on Iran That Goes Beyond Bombs</em></a></p>



<p>The crackdown began with an internet blackout on Jan. 8, plunging the country into an information darkness and preventing humanitarian groups and governments alike from understanding the full extent of the killing.</p>



<p>According to human rights groups, protesters were killed by security forces en masse. Throughout the blackout, IHR estimates that more than 20,000 people have been arrested in connection with the protests.</p>



<p>That blackout has made an accurate death toll difficult to ascertain, as humanitarian groups struggle to reach contacts on the ground. But as early as last week, an informal group of academics and professionals working at hospitals and <a href="https://time.com/7345347/iran-protests-death-toll-estimate-thousands/" >contacted by TIME</a> said protester deaths between Jan. 8 and Jan. 10 alone could have reached 6,000. </p>



<p>In a video address Saturday, Khamenei said &ldquo;thousands&rdquo; had died in the protests, &ldquo;some in an inhuman, savage manner.&rdquo; He blamed the United States and President Donald Trump for the extent of destruction, calling him a &ldquo;criminal&#8221;.</p>



<p>&#8220;We will not drag the country into war, but we will not let domestic or international criminals go unpunished,&#8221; Khamenei said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Trump has hinted in recent days that he came close to authorizing military strikes against Iran over the crackdown. He spent days last week threatening Iran&rsquo;s leaders if the crackdown continued, and on Jan. 13 <a href="https://time.com/7345860/trump-iran-military-strikes/" >declared</a>, &ldquo;help is on its way.&rdquo;</p>



<p>He was reportedly <a href="https://www.axios.com/2026/01/18/iran-strikes-trump-delay-military-options"  target="_blank">presented with</a> military options to strike Iran on Tuesday, but by Friday, he appeared to have decided against the move after claiming that Iran had canceled some 800 executions of protesters it had planned.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The best decision he ever made was not hanging more than 800 people two days ago,&rdquo; Trump told <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2026/01/17/trump-to-politico-its-time-to-look-for-new-leadership-in-iran-00735528"  target="_blank">POLITICO</a> about Iran&#8217;s Supreme Leader on Saturday.&nbsp;</p>



<p>But in that same interview, Trump reacted with anger over Khamenei&rsquo;s remarks that blamed Trump for the high death toll in Iran.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s time to look for new leadership in Iran,&rdquo; he declared.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Trump said Khamenei &ldquo;should focus on running his country properly, like I do with the United States, and not killing people by the thousands in order to keep control.&rdquo;</p>



<p>It is unclear whether Trump is still considering military action against Iran. <span style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Several <a href="https://www.foxnews.com/world/us-sending-military-assets-middle-east-trump-weighs-iran-strike-sources-say"  target="_blank" target="_blank">news outlets</a> reported on Friday that the aircraft carrier US</span>S Abraham Lincoln was heading towards the Middle East and would arrive in approximately one week. </p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347170</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Europe Promises United Response to Trump’s ‘Dangerous’ Greenland Tariffs</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347149/greenland-tariffs/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Richard Hall and Rebecca Schneid]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 18 Jan 2026 14:40:01 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347149</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Eight countries issued a statement declaring that they “stand in full solidarity with the Kingdom of Denmark and the people of Greenland.”]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347149"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347149/greenland-tariffs/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/AP26017638341199.jpg" alt="Greenland US Protest"/>



<p>Europe vowed a united response after President Donald Trump said he would impose tariffs on eight of its allies for sending troops to Greenland, an autonomous territory of Denmark that the president has repeatedly <a href="https://time.com/7347049/greenland-trump-annexation-threats-world-leaders/" >threatened to annex</a>.</p>



[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]

<p>Trump said Saturday he would introduce 10% tariffs on imports from Denmark, Norway, Sweden, France, Germany, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Finland, all of which sent small numbers of military personnel to Greenland in recent days to <a href="https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/" >take part in military exercises</a>.</p>



<p>The move, which comes as Trump has stepped up his campaign to annex the territory, prompted a wave of condemnation from the leaders of the ostensible U.S. allies, which were already subject to tariffs of 10% and 15%. The row could call into question trade deals the U.S. struck with the U.K. in May and the European Union in July.</p>



<p><strong>Read more:</strong> <a href="https://time.com/7345949/greenland-denmark-trump/" ><em>On Eve of Crunch Talks with U.S., Greenland Declares: &lsquo;We Choose Denmark&rsquo;</em></a></p>



<p>On Sunday, the eight countries issued a joint statement declaring that they &ldquo;stand in full solidarity with the Kingdom of Denmark and the people of Greenland.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;As members of Nato, we are committed to strengthening Arctic security as a shared transatlantic interest. The pre-coordinated Danish exercise Arctic Endurance conducted with Allies, responds to this necessity. It poses no threat to anyone,&rdquo; the statement said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;Tariff threats undermine transatlantic relations and risk a dangerous downward spiral. We will continue to stand united and coordinated in our response. We are committed to upholding our sovereignty,&#8221; it added.&nbsp;</p>



<p>A day earlier, Trump&rsquo;s announcement set off a firestorm across European capitals as he threatened tariffs in his latest effort to acquire the territory of Greenland for the United States. </p>



<p>&ldquo;Denmark, Norway, Sweden, France, Germany, The United Kingdom, The Netherlands, and Finland have journeyed to Greenland, for purposes unknown. This is a very dangerous situation for the Safety, Security, and Survival of our Planet,&rdquo; Trump said in a Truth Social <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115911344443637897"  target="_blank">post Saturday</a> announcing the tariffs.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Trump added that the tariffs would increase to 25% on June 1, and would remain in effect &ldquo;until such time as a Deal is reached for the Complete and Total purchase of Greenland.&rdquo;</p>



<p>His comments came as thousands rallied on Saturday in the Danish cities of Copenhagen, Aarhus, Aalborg and Odense, as well as in Greenland&rsquo;s capital, Nuuk, to oppose Trump&rsquo;s annexation plans. In Nuuk, hundreds marched to the U.S. consulate, some <a href="https://x.com/carlbildt/status/2012574191241818589"  target="_blank">holding signs</a> that read &ldquo;Greenland is not for sale,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Yankees go home!&rdquo;</p>



<p>The tariff announcement drew unusually blunt reactions from the leaders of some of America&#8217;s closest allies on Saturday.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;Applying tariffs on allies for pursuing the collective security of NATO allies is completely wrong,&#8221; British Prime Minister Keir Starmer said, adding that he would raise the issue directly with the White House.</p>



<p>&#8220;Our position on Greenland is very clear&mdash;it is part of the Kingdom of Denmark and its future is a matter for the Greenlanders and the Danes,&#8221; he continued.</p>



<p>French President Emmanuel Macron called the tariffs &#8220;unacceptable.&#8221;</p>



<p>&#8220;No intimidation nor threat will influence us, neither in Ukraine, nor in Greenland, nor anywhere else in the world when we are confronted with such situations,&#8221; he said.</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s threat is likely to prompt a reciprocal response from Europe. The European Union summoned ambassadors to an emergency meeting in Brussels on Sunday, and Reuters reported the bloc could suspend its work on a U.S. trade deal it struck in July. </p>



<p>European Council President Antonio Costa said <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-vows-response-to-new-trump-tariffs-over-greenland/"  target="_blank">Saturday</a> he was &#8220;coordinating a joint response from the European Union&#8217;s member states on this issue.&#8221; </p>



<p>Speaking on Sunday, German finance minister and vice chancellor Lars Klingbeil said: &#8220;And so the very clear signal: we will not be blackmailed, and there will be a European response.&#8221;</p>



<p>Trump has argued that anything less than total U.S. control of Greenland would be &ldquo;unacceptable, &rdquo; and has said that annexing the territory is necessary for &ldquo;national security.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>European nations, meanwhile, have strongly opposed the U.S. takeover of Greenland. </p>



<p>Earlier this week, Denmark increased its military presence on the island and conducted joint military exercises with the European allies targeted by Trump&rsquo;s tariffs.</p>



<p>Denmark&rsquo;s foreign minister, Lars L&oslash;kke Rasmussen, told reporters during a visit to Washington this week that Denmark was reinforcing security in the Arctic &ldquo;by committing additional funds for military capabilities&mdash;not dogsleds, but ships, drones, fighter jets, etc,&rdquo; referring to an often-repeated jibe by Trump that Denmark&rsquo;s military presence on the island consisted entirely of dogsleds.</p>



<p>Several European NATO allies announced they were also sending military personnel to the island after Danish representatives emerged from meetings at the White House, declaring they had &#8220;fundamental disagreements&#8221; with the Trump administration over who should control Greenland.</p>



<p>Announcing France&rsquo;s involvement in the military exercises in Greenland, Macron took aim at Trump&rsquo;s ambitions.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We live in a world where destabilizing powers have awakened,&rdquo; Macron said.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We are seeing certainties that sometimes lasted for decades being called into question, and Europe is being shaken in some of its certainties,&rdquo; he said. Europe &ldquo;sometimes has allies that we thought were predictable, always by our side, who are now causing us to have serious doubts, or even turning on those who doubted the least.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The United Kingdom, Germany, Sweden and Norway have also sent troops to take part in the military exercise, Operation Arctic Endurance.</p>



<p>Greenland&rsquo;s leaders and people have been clear in their opposition to the possibility of the U.S. taking control of the territory. Greenland&rsquo;s Prime Minister Jens-Frederik Nielsen said this week that the island would <a href="https://time.com/7345949/greenland-denmark-trump/" >choose Denmark</a> over the U.S. if it had to choose, while polls show that Greenlanders overwhelmingly oppose the idea of becoming part of the U.S.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Our country is not an object of superpower rhetoric. We are a people. A land. And democracy,&rdquo; Nielsen said earlier this month. &ldquo;This has to be respected. Especially by close and loyal friends.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump has frequently used tariffs as a <a href="https://time.com/7305626/chaotic-world-of-trumps-tariffs/" >foreign policy tool</a> during his second term, negotiating deals with India, China, and the U.K. to lower tariffs in exchange for concessions on his policy priorities.&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347149</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Trump Calls for ‘New Leadership’ in Iran After Reading Social Media Posts By Supreme Leader</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347132/trump-khamenei-iran-protests/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Richard Hall]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 17 Jan 2026 20:47:44 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347132</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Trump made the call after being read a series of posts on X by Khamenei that attacked him, POLITICO reported. ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347132"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7347132/trump-khamenei-iran-protests/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/AP24203688879577.jpg" alt="Ayatollah Ali Khamenei"/>



<p>President Donald Trump called for &ldquo;new leadership&rdquo; in Iran after reading a series of social media posts from the country&rsquo;s Supreme Leader, Ali Khamenei, on Saturday, <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2026/01/17/trump-to-politico-its-time-to-look-for-new-leadership-in-iran-00735528?"  target="_blank">POLITICO</a> reported.</p>



<p>The remarks represent the latest in a series of <a href="https://time.com/7345860/trump-iran-military-strikes/" >sharp shifts in tone</a> from the president with regard to Iran&rsquo;s leadership in the last week, as he has weighed military intervention in response to a crackdown that has killed thousands of protesters. </p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Trump&#8217;s comments came during an interview with POLITICO in which he was read a series of <a href="https://x.com/khamenei_ir/status/2012468046225424434?s=20"  target="_blank">posts</a> from Khamenei on X on Saturday that blamed Trump for the deaths of protesters in Iran.</p>



<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s time to look for new leadership in Iran,&rdquo; Trump said in response.</p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7345555/iran-protests-deaths-us-trump-israel/" ><em>What&rsquo;s Happening in Iran Right Now, Explained</em></a></p>



<p>&ldquo;What he is guilty of, as the leader of a country, is the complete destruction of the country and the use of violence at levels never seen before,&rdquo; Trump continued. &ldquo;In order to keep the country functioning &mdash; even though that function is a very low level &mdash; the leadership should focus on running his country properly, like I do with the United States, and not killing people by the thousands in order to keep control.&rdquo;</p>



<p>In a series of missives posted on Saturday, Khamenei blamed Trump for the violence in Iran and said the U.S. &ldquo;must be held accountable.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We find the US President guilty due to the casualties, damages and slander he inflicted upon the Iranian nation,&rdquo; <a href="https://x.com/khamenei_ir/status/2012468046225424434?s=20"  target="_blank">Khamenei wrote</a>.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The US had made extensive preparations to orchestrate this sedition. This sedition was a prelude to even bigger schemes. The Iranian nation defeated the US,&rdquo; he wrote in another.&nbsp;</p>



<p>It is not clear who read the posts to Trump, but the president&rsquo;s reaction is a sign of the fragility of the current peace between the U.S. and Iran. Trump said he had been presented with a number of &ldquo;very strong options&rdquo; to strike Iran last week after the death toll from the crackdown on protests reached the hundreds.</p>



<p>On Tuesday, as the death toll crept higher into the thousands, it appeared Trump was on the brink of authorizing strikes when he told protesters that &ldquo;help was on its way.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&#8220;Iranian Patriots, KEEP PROTESTING &#8211; TAKE OVER YOUR INSTITUTIONS!!!&#8221; Trump wrote in a post on Truth Social. &#8220;Save the names of the killers and abusers. They will pay a big price. I have cancelled all meetings with Iranian Officials until the senseless killing of protesters STOPS. HELP IS ON ITS WAY.&#8221;</p>



<p>By Friday, however, Trump&rsquo;s tone suddenly changed when he thanked Iran&#8217;s leaders for apparently cancelling 800 executions, without providing evidence.</p>



<p>&ldquo;I greatly respect the fact that all scheduled hangings, which were to take place yesterday (Over 800 of them), have been cancelled by the leadership of Iran. Thank you!&rdquo; Trump <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115906000981082082"  target="_blank">posted Friday</a> on Truth Social.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The U.S.-based Human Rights Activists News Agency, or HRANA, said it had verified 3,090 deaths in Iran, including 2,885 protesters, and over 22,000 arrests.</p>



<p>The White House did not respond to a request for comment. <br></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
