		<item>
		<title>‘He Doesn&#8217;t Care About Us’: Iranian Protesters Say They Were Betrayed By Trump</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347090/iran-protesters-trump-help/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Kay Armin Serjoie]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 17 Jan 2026 17:20:46 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347090</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Protesters were heartened when Trump promised help was ‘on its way.’ Now, they feel betrayed by his lack of action.  ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347090"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347090/iran-protesters-trump-help/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255957509.jpg" alt="Unrest In Iran As Protesters Demonstrate Over Economic Crisis"/>



<p>When President Donald Trump told protesters in Iran that &ldquo;<a href="https://time.com/7345860/trump-iran-military-strikes/" >help is on its way</a>,&rdquo; they took heart. Their hopes rose further on Wednesday, with news that the Pentagon had ordered some non-essential personnel from its largest Middle East air base, a move seen as preparation for battle. But on Thursday, when Trump reversed course, announcing that Iran&rsquo;s regime had agreed to stop killing its people in the streets, protestors felt betrayed, they told TIME.<br><br>&ldquo;He&#8217;s not only yellow on the outside, he&#8217;s also yellow inside,&rdquo; said an arts teacher in Tehran.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>&ldquo;After he said the Iranian authorities had told him there won&rsquo;t be any more killings and executions, everyone was just stunned,&rdquo; said an Iranian <a href="https://time.com/7346661/trump-iran-military-strikes-diplomacy-sanctions/" >interviewed Friday</a>, after traveling out of the country. &ldquo;Everyone was enraged; they just kept saying this bastard used us as cannon fodder. Iranians feel that they were played, that he fooled them, deceived them.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7345555/iran-protests-deaths-us-trump-israel/" ><em>What&rsquo;s Happening in Iran Right Now, Explained</em></a></p>



<p>&ldquo;Trump is worse than Obama,&rdquo; said a 40-year-old businessman in Tehran, who said he called friends and relatives to give them the good news after Trump&rsquo;s&nbsp; &ldquo;help is on its way&rdquo; post.&nbsp; &ldquo;He screwed up. He pulled the rug from under our feet.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The interviews were conducted after Trump appeared to back down from carrying out long-threatened military action against Iran this week. But the President added to the uncertainty again on Saturday by calling for an end to the rule of Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.</p>



<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s time to look for new leadership in Iran,&rdquo; he told POLITICO, after reportedly reading a series of posts from the Iranian leader blaming Trump for the deaths of protesters. &ldquo;The man is a sick man who should run his country properly and stop killing people,&rdquo; he added. </p>



<p>His comments may not be enough to bring protesters back out onto the streets, however. Trump, who ordered the U.S. military to join Israel in attacking Iran&rsquo;s nuclear program in June, had urged on the latest protests nearly from the start. The demonstrations began in Tehran&rsquo;s Grand Bazaar on Dec. 28, in response to the abrupt, catastrophic devaluation of Iran&rsquo;s currency, then grew steadily across the country. In the past&mdash;2009, 2017, 2019, and 2022&mdash;Iran&rsquo;s authoritarian regime had crushed mass protests. But five days into this outbreak,  on Jan. 2, Trump made an explicit promise on <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115824439366264186"  target="_blank">Truth Social</a>: &ldquo;If Iran shots [sic] and violently kills peaceful protestors, the United States of America will come to their rescue. We are locked and loaded and ready to go.&rdquo; </p>



<p>Iranians took heart. On Jan. 8, at the start of the Iranian weekend and following calls by Iran&rsquo;s exiled crown prince Reza Pahlavi and other opposition groups, millions took to the streets across the country.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">&#8216;Trump is responsible&#8217;</h2>



<p>The regime, in turn, responded with extreme violence. First, as it has done in the past before directing live fire into groups of its own citizens, it disconnected the nation of 90 million from the internet, then cut cell phone, SMS and land lines. Security forces then mounted an onslaught that left &ldquo;thousands dead&rdquo;, according to Khamenei, in remarks carried by the state TV Saturday.<br><br>&ldquo;When I saw the man a few metres ahead of me fall backwards, I didn&rsquo;t understand what had happened,&rdquo; said the businessman, describing a scene on Jan. 8 on a Tehran street. &ldquo;When we gathered around him, all I could see in the dark night was a red spot on his forehead. It was only when the blood from the back of his head pooled at our feet that we realized he&rsquo;d been shot by a sniper.&rdquo;</p>



<p>While the Iranian regime ordered the attacks, &ldquo;Trump is also responsible for the death of these 15,000,&rdquo; he said, quoting one estimate of the dead. &ldquo;Because many of the protesters took to the streets when they saw his post that the US is locked and loaded.&rdquo; He said that the U.S. must have made a deal with the Islamic Republic &ldquo;to betray Iranians like this.&#8221;</p>



<p>The killings occurred across the country. In the northern city of Zirab, a 39-year-old man said that, on the next day, Jan. 9, protestors were forced down a street only to see the way ahead blocked, with security forces at their back. &ldquo;Then the streetlights went out, and machine guns started shooting,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Nothing could be seen, everyone was falling down, either from bullets or not seeing ahead of them, trying to get away.&rdquo; The resident said he doesn&rsquo;t know how many were killed, but that in the next few days there were as many as 17 missing in the city of a few thousand.<br><br>Iran&rsquo;s rulers publicly gloated over Trump&rsquo;s reversal. On Friday, Trump thanked them for promising to stop the planned executions of 800 protestors, the assurance he had offered as grounds for withholding the military action so widely expected that international flights steered around Iranian airspace.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2254948920_cb59eb.jpg" alt="Protests in Iran January 2026" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>&#8220;Trump says a lot of nonsense and gibberish,&rdquo; Tehran&rsquo;s prosecutor, Ali Salehi, replied on Saturday, according to state TV. &ldquo;Our reaction will be forceful, preventive and swift. Indictments have been issued for numerous cases and sent to courts.&#8221;</p>



<p>Iranians say they are already living with the consequences of Trump&rsquo;s reversal. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s already martial law,&rdquo; said a woman in Tehran. &ldquo;Now, after Trump went back on his word, they&rsquo;ve become even more brazen. I saw a checkpoint on Marzdaran Boulevard where they were checking the cellphones of people.</p>



<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve lost all hope,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Trump&rsquo;s not going to do anything. Why should he? He doesn&rsquo;t care about us.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">&#8216;He is tricking the regime&#8217; </h2>



<p>Others say they retain hope that Trump still might act. &ldquo;My husband believes that this is Trump&rsquo;s usual pattern, to confuse them [the Islamic Republic],&rdquo; said the Tehran resident. &ldquo;He says if Trump does not attack, how can the regime be toppled? Iranians are doing everything they can, but the regime is just too savage.&rdquo;<br><br>&ldquo;He is tricking the regime,&rdquo; said an engineer in Tehran, who also sees Trump&rsquo;s reversal as tactical. &ldquo;He&rsquo;ll attack, and attack hard. He&rsquo;s going to go after Zahhak himself,&rdquo; the engineer said, referring to the name of the most evil character in Iranian mythology, used by protestors to describe Khamenei. &ldquo;There can&rsquo;t be any other option,&rdquo; he added. &ldquo;It&#8217;s different this time.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The businessman also hopes that this uprising will be different, so much so that he stayed behind in Iran when his wife and child flew out of the country on Thursday. But he says the protesters would need help. &ldquo;The people on the streets did all they could do. We were facing machine guns on pick-up trucks, empty-handed. The only way we can win is with foreign intervention, like Kosovo or Bosnia.&#8221;</p>



<p>Whatever Trump ultimately decides to do, most people in Iran agree that the protests have gone underground.</p>



<p>&nbsp;&ldquo;Right now the uprising is paralyzed,&rdquo; said the man from Zirab, who put the blame on Trump as well as the brutality of the regime. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know if it will ever recover.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347090</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>What World Leaders Have Said About Trump’s Threats to Annex Greenland</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347049/greenland-trump-annexation-threats-world-leaders/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Chantelle Lee]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 17 Jan 2026 00:17:04 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347049</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Many leaders have pushed back on Trump's plans to take over Greenland.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347049"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347049/greenland-trump-annexation-threats-world-leaders/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/World-Leaders-Respond-Greenland.jpg" alt="Greenland's Prime Minister At New Year's Reception In Copenhagen"/>



<p>As President Donald Trump has renewed <a href="https://time.com/7344877/trump-greenland-annexation-threats-purchase-national-security-economic/" >his push to annex Greenland</a> in recent weeks, many world leaders have raised vocal objections.</p>



<p>Greenland is an autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark. But Trump has claimed that the U.S. needs to take control of the island for &ldquo;national security&rdquo; reasons and that the European Union also &ldquo;needs&rdquo; the U.S. to annex the territory. The Trump Administration has suggested the possibility of using military force to acquire Greenland; White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt said earlier this month that &ldquo;utilizing the U.S. military is always an option at the Commander-in-Chief&rsquo;s disposal.&rdquo; And on Friday, Trump indicated that he may <a href="https://time.com/7346949/trump-greenland-tariffs-threat/" >impose tariffs</a> on nations that &ldquo;don&rsquo;t go along with&rdquo; his plans for the territory.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Many European leaders, as well as other political figures around the world, have pushed back on Trump&rsquo;s plans to take over Greenland, however&mdash;and warned that an attack on the territory could have major consequences for the international world order.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Here&rsquo;s what world leaders have said on the issue.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Greenland</strong></h2>



<p>Greenland&rsquo;s Prime Minister Jens-Frederik Nielsen <a href="https://time.com/7343110/trump-greenland-annex-threats-nielsen-responds/" >voiced his strong opposition</a> to the possibility of the U.S. taking control of the territory in a social media post earlier this month.</p>



<p>&ldquo;When the President of the United States talks about &lsquo;we need Greenland&rsquo; and connects us with Venezuela and military intervention, it&rsquo;s not just wrong, it&rsquo;s so disrespectful,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Our country is not an object of superpower rhetoric. We are a people. A land. And democracy. This has to be respected. Especially by close and loyal friends.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The leaders of the territory&rsquo;s five political parties, including Nielsen, also <a href="https://time.com/7345221/trump-greenland-statement-denmark/" >released</a> a joint statement last week in which they rejected Trump&rsquo;s remarks on the island by saying, &ldquo;We do not want to be Americans, we do not want to be Danes, we want to be Greenlanders.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>On Tuesday, Nielsen again rebuked Trump, <a href="https://time.com/7345949/greenland-denmark-trump/" >saying</a> at a press conference, &ldquo;We are now facing a geopolitical crisis, and if we have to choose between the United States and Denmark here and now, we choose Denmark.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Denmark</strong></h2>



<p>Danish Prime Minister Mette Frederiksen <a href="https://apnews.com/article/denmark-greenland-trump-2b12bb104faaaafda2ed270febfb0522"  target="_blank">told</a> broadcasters in her country this month that Trump&rsquo;s comments about taking control of Greenland &#8220;should be taken seriously.&rdquo; Frederiksen also warned that &ldquo;If the United States chooses to attack another NATO country militarily, then everything stops,&rdquo; saying that such an aggressive action would mark the end of NATO.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We will not accept a situation where we and Greenland are threatened in this way,&rdquo; she said.</p>



<p>On Wednesday, Denmark said that it was <a href="https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/" >strengthening its military presence</a> on and around the island.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>France</strong></h2>



<p>In December, French President Emmanuel Macron <a href="https://x.com/EmmanuelMacron/status/2003391697808732561"  target="_blank">posted</a> on X that he &ldquo;reaffirmed France&rsquo;s unwavering support for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Denmark and Greenland,&rdquo; adding that &ldquo;Greenland belongs to its people. Denmark stands as its guarantor.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Earlier this month, Macron joined six other European leaders, including Frederiksen, in signing a <a href="https://stm.dk/statsministeriet/publikationer/faellesudtalelse-om-groenland/"  target="_blank">joint statement</a> that said, &ldquo;Greenland belongs to its people. It is for Denmark and Greenland, and them only, to decide on matters concerning Denmark and Greenland.&rdquo;</p>



<p>France was also among several European allies that dispatched military personnel to Greenland; Macron <a href="https://x.com/EmmanuelMacron/status/2011578747791819017"  target="_blank">said</a> on Wednesday that French military troops were &ldquo;already on their way&rdquo; there, and that more would arrive in the coming days.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Italy</strong></h2>



<p><a href="https://time.com/7304882/giorgia-meloni-interview/" >Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni</a> was among the seven European leaders who signed onto the joint statement earlier this month that defended Greenland&rsquo;s sovereignty. Last week, she <a href="https://apnews.com/article/italy-meloni-trump-us-greenland-denmark-military-action-c15bb5780c64f41fd44417599c10b7c9"  target="_blank">said</a> that she didn&rsquo;t believe the Trump Administration would take military action to annex the territory, adding that Italy wouldn&rsquo;t back an operation like that.</p>



<p>Meloni, one of Trump&rsquo;s closest allies on the continent, emphasized that &ldquo;international law must be fully defended,&rdquo; though when a reporter asked her about Trump&rsquo;s policies, she replied, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t understand what you&rsquo;re asking when you say Italy must distance itself from the United States.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Poland</strong></h2>



<p>Polish Prime Minister Donald Tusk also signed onto the joint statement by European leaders this month.&nbsp;</p>



<p>On Thursday, Tusk said that Poland won&rsquo;t send military troops to Greenland, unlike some other European allies. But he cautioned that a U.S. military operation there would be calamitous.</p>



<p>&ldquo;An attempt to take over (part of) a NATO member state by another NATO member state would be a political disaster,&rdquo; he <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/poland-will-not-send-soldiers-greenland-polish-pm-says-2026-01-15/"  target="_blank">said</a> at a press conference. &ldquo;It would be the end of the world as we know it, which guaranteed a world based on NATO solidarity, which held back the evil forces associated with communist terror or other forms of aggression.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Spain</strong></h2>



<p>Spanish Prime Minister Pedro S&aacute;nchez defended Greenland&rsquo;s sovereignty in a <a href="https://x.com/sanchezcastejon/status/2003432652439962067"  target="_blank">post</a> on X in December.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Respecting sovereignty and territorial integrity is central to the EU and to all nations of the world. Security in the Arctic is a priority on which we seek to work with allies and partners,&rdquo; he wrote. &ldquo;We convey our full solidarity with Denmark and the people of Greenland.&rdquo;</p>



<p>S&aacute;nchez also joined the other European leaders in signing the statement earlier this month that supported Greenland&rsquo;s sovereignty.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Germany</strong></h2>



<p>German Chancellor Friedrich Merz was among the European leaders who signed the joint statement this month, and Germany was one of several allied European countries that said they would send military personnel to the territory.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>The United Kingdom</strong></h2>



<p><a href="https://time.com/collections/100-most-influential-people-2025/7273780/keir-starmer/" >U.K. Prime Minister Keir Starmer</a>, who was among the seven European leaders to sign onto the joint statement, has also reaffirmed Greenland&rsquo;s sovereignty.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Greenland and the Kingdom of Denmark must decide the future of Greenland and only Greenland and the Kingdom of Denmark,&rdquo; he told the <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cy9yq8znq37o"  target="_blank">BBC</a> earlier this month.</p>



<p>One British military officer is being sent to Greenland, along with troops from other European allies, &ldquo;at the request of the Danish government,&rdquo; U.K. Defense Secretary John Healey <a href="https://www.thetimes.com/world/europe/article/uk-troops-greenland-nato-military-operation-jjfpfmvg8?gaa_at=eafs&amp;gaa_n=AWEtsqfCg8snFp__l9mEK0UdJbM2McjnLBkTkJd_GcWLgHPUJPJaypnfcfo-Bxn3l80%3D&amp;gaa_ts=696acebb&amp;gaa_sig=721LSXEOCI8rMrQ7zN-XJfEEyJodcNvyE1HhNnGqRYk6Yp9HMI6VEWkVapXMpxFc15AVGlgWrkJvEH3EGjO4LQ%3D%3D"  target="_blank">said</a> this week.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Sweden</strong></h2>



<p>Sweden&rsquo;s Prime Minister Ulf Kristersson <a href="https://x.com/SwedishPM/status/2011135599584166043"  target="_blank">said</a> in a post on X on Tuesday that &ldquo;We stand behind Denmark and Greenland.&rdquo; The following day, he <a href="https://x.com/SwedishPM/status/2011469780729868447?s=20"  target="_blank">announced</a> that several officers from the Swedish Armed Forces would arrive in Greenland shortly, as part of a group from several allied nations and at the request of Denmark.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Canada</strong></h2>



<p>Speaking to reporters at a press conference in Beijing on Friday, Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/carney-to-trump-back-off-greenland/"  target="_blank">backed</a> Denmark and Greenland.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The future of Greenland is a decision for Greenland and for the Kingdom of Denmark,&rdquo; Carney said, calling on NATO allies to &ldquo;respect their commitments.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347049</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Can a Nobel Prize Be Gifted or Sold? Venezuela’s Machado Isn’t the First Winner to Give Their Medal Away</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7347040/nobel-peace-prize-trump-venezuela-machado-sold-gift-history/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Connor Greene]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Jan 2026 23:49:22 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7347040</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Venezuelan opposition leader María Corina Machado isn't the first Nobel Prize winner to give their medal away.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7347040"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7347040/nobel-peace-prize-trump-venezuela-machado-sold-gift-history/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2256475497.jpg" alt="President Trump Meets With Venezuelan Opposition Leader And Nobel Peace Prize Winner Mar&iacute;a Corina Machado At The White House"/>



<p>Nobel Prizes are not transferable. But that hasn&rsquo;t stopped a number of recipients or their family members from donating, selling, or&mdash;in some cases&mdash;trying and failing to sell their medals over the years.</p>

[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]



<p>Venezuelan opposition leader Mar&iacute;a Corina Machado became the latest of the prestigious awards&rsquo; winners to join that list on Thursday, <a href="https://time.com/7346654/machado-trump-meeting-nobel-prize-venezuela/" >gifting her 2025 Nobel Peace Prize medal</a> to President Donald Trump while meeting with him at the White House in the wake of U.S. forces <a href="https://time.com/7342941/venezuela-maduro-bombing-trump-delta-force/" >capturing</a> Venezuelan President Nicol&aacute;s Maduro. </p>



<p>Machado <a href="https://x.com/FoxNews/status/2011982499509846355"  target="_blank">told</a> Fox News that she gave the medal to Trump, who has long coveted the Peace prize and openly campaigned for it before it was awarded to the Venezuelan opposition leader, because &ldquo;he deserves it.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&#8220;I decided to present the Nobel Peace Prize medal on behalf of the people of Venezuela,&#8221; she said.</p>



<p><strong>Read more: </strong><em><a href="https://time.com/7346981/machado-venezuela-democracy-trump-nobel-prize/" >Machado Insists Trump Will Do What&rsquo;s Needed to Turn Venezuela Into a Democracy</a></em></p>



<p>The move has drawn criticism from some <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/16/maria-corina-machado-giving-trump-nobel-peace-prize-medal-absurd-say-norwegian-politicians"  target="_blank">politicians</a> in Norway, where the prize is awarded. The Nobel committee itself clarified that &#8220;the Nobel Prize and the laureate are inseparable.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;Regardless of what may happen to the medal, the diploma, or the prize money, it is and remains the original laureate who is recorded in history as the recipient of the prize,&rdquo; the Nobel committee <a href="https://www.nobelpeaceprize.org/press/press-releases/the-nobel-prize-and-the-laureate-are-inseparable"  target="_blank">wrote</a> in a pointedly timed Friday press release. &ldquo;Even if the medal or diploma later comes into someone else&rsquo;s possession, this does not alter who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Here are some other notable recipients of the Nobel Prize who decided not to keep their medals&mdash;and what they did with them, or tried to.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Dmitry Muratov (Peace)</strong></h2>



<p>The Russian journalist won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2021 for fighting for press freedom and standing up to Russian authorities.&nbsp;</p>



<p>He sold his medal the following year at auction for $103.5 million, which he gave to UNICEF&rsquo;s fund for Ukrainian refugee children. This is the highest price ever paid for a Nobel Prize medal.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Kofi Annan (Peace)</strong></h2>



<p>The former secretary-general of the United Nations was a co-recipient of the Peace prize in 2001. He was given the honor for his prioritization of human rights and for &ldquo;his commitment to the struggle to contain the spreading of the HIV virus in Africa and his declared opposition to international terrorism,&rdquo; according to the Nobel Foundation.</p>



<p>Following Annan&rsquo;s death in 2018, his widow, Nane Annan, donated his medal in 2024 to the United Nations&rsquo; office in Geneva so that, she said, his legacy could continue inspiring future generations. The medal remains on permanent display there.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Christian Lous Lange (Peace)</strong></h2>



<p>Lange, Norway&rsquo;s first Nobel Peace Prize laureate, received the honor in 1921 along with the Swede Hjalmar Branting for what the committee <a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/1921/summary/"  target="_blank">described</a> as &ldquo;their lifelong contributions to the cause of peace and organized internationalism.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Both Lange and Branting &ldquo;wanted to strengthen the new world organization the League of Nations,&rdquo; according to the Nobel Foundation. Branting was Sweden&rsquo;s Prime Minister at the time they were awarded the prize, while Lange became secretary-general of the Inter-Parliamentary Union&mdash;an international organization of national parliaments&mdash;in 1909 and managed the organization through the first World War. Lange later went on to become a member of the Nobel Committee in 1934.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The Lange family has loaned the prize to the Nobel Peace Center in Oslo, where it has been since 2005. It is the only original peace prize permanently on public display in Norway.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Carlos Saavedra Lamas (Peace)</strong></h2>



<p>The foreign minister of Argentina received the Peace prize in 1936 for his part in ending the Chaco War between Bolivia and Paraguay. His medal was sold at auction for $1.1 million to a private Asian buyer. The estate of another private collector in New York, who had owned it for roughly a decade, made the sale.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>James Watson and Francis Crick (Medicine)</strong></h2>



<p>Watson and Crick, along with Maurice Wilkins, were awarded the 1962 prize in Medicine for discovering the double-helix structure of DNA in 1953, a breakthrough that propelled the field of molecular biology.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The medal awarded to Crick, who died in 2004, was sold at auction by his heirs for $2 million in 2013 to Shanghai biotech executive Jack Wang.</p>



<p><strong>Read more: </strong><em><a href="https://time.com/5524001/james-watson-dna-death-obituary/" >James Watson, Co-Discoverer of DNA&rsquo;s Double Helix, Leaves Behind a Troubling Legacy</a></em></p>



<p>Watson sold his own medal the following year for $4.76 million to Russian billionaire Alisher Usmanov, who later gave the prize back to the laureate. Watson died last year on Nov. 6. </p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>William Faulkner</strong> <strong>(Literature)</strong></h2>



<p>The author, known for modernist Southern Gothic classics including <em>The Sound and the Fury </em>and <em>As I Lay Dying</em>, won the Literature prize in 1949 for what the committee described as &ldquo;his powerful and artistically unique contribution to the modern American novel.&#8221; His medal went up for auction in 2016, but failed to sell: Bidding came to a stop at $425,000, failing to reach the minimum bid.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Knut Hamsun (Literature)</strong></h2>



<p>The current location of Hamsun&rsquo;s medal is unknown. The winner of the 1920 Literature prize&mdash;a Norwegian writer who received the award for <em>Growth of the Soil</em>, a 1917 novel that tells the story of a man settling and cultivating a farm in rural Norway<em> </em>that the Nobel committee called a &ldquo;monumental work&rdquo;&mdash;sold his medal to German Propaganda Minister Joseph Goebbels as a gesture of thanks after meeting with him in 1943.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Leon Lederman (Physics)</strong></h2>



<p>Lederman, who was a co-recipient of the Physics prize in 1988 for the discovery of a second type of neutrino, sold his medal in 2015 for $765,002 to cover medical expenses to treat his dementia.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>David Thouless (Physics)</strong></h2>



<p>Thouless won the Physics prize in 2016 alongside two other British scientists for using a branch of mathematics known as topology to explain what happens when matter changes phases. His family donated the medal to Trinity Hall at the University of Cambridge, where it is displayed for students.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7347040</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Machado Insists Trump Will Do What’s Needed to Turn Venezuela Into a Democracy</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346981/machado-venezuela-democracy-trump-nobel-prize/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Nik Popli]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Jan 2026 19:27:49 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venezuela]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346981</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[“Venezuela is going to be free,” Machado said]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346981"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7346981/machado-venezuela-democracy-trump-nobel-prize/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255970107.jpg" alt="US-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-DIPLOMACY-MACHADO"/>



<p>A day after she gave President Donald Trump <a href="https://time.com/7346654/machado-trump-meeting-nobel-prize-venezuela/" >her Nobel Peace Prize medal</a>, Venezuelan opposition leader Mar&iacute;a Corina Machado insisted that her country was on an irreversible path toward democracy, even as Trump has spoken far more frequently in recent days about securing Venezuelan oil than bringing about free elections.</p>

[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]



<p>Speaking at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank in Washington, Machado said she was &ldquo;profoundly confident&rdquo; that Venezuela would see an orderly transition and, eventually, free and fair elections, and that she trusted Trump to do what was necessary to make that happen.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Venezuela is going to be free,&rdquo; Machado said, adding that freedom would be achieved &ldquo;with the support of the people of the United States and President Donald Trump.&rdquo; She described the moment as the &ldquo;first steps of a true transition to democracy,&rdquo; while acknowledging that the process ahead would be &ldquo;very complex and difficult.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Her confidence stood in contrast to the Trump Administration&rsquo;s actions in Venezuela following the <a href="https://time.com/7342941/venezuela-maduro-bombing-trump-delta-force/" >Jan. 3 raid</a> that removed Nicol&aacute;s Maduro and sent him to the United States to face narco-trafficking charges. In the two weeks since, Trump has backed former Maduro loyalists&mdash;led by interim President Delcy Rodr&iacute;guez&mdash;to govern Venezuela in the short term, and has given little detail of plans to transition Venezuela into a democracy. Administration officials have argued that Rodr&iacute;guez represents the most stable option for maintaining order and ensuring cooperation, particularly on securing <a href="https://time.com/7346460/venezuela-oil-us-first-sale/" >Venezuela&rsquo;s vast energy reserves</a>.</p>



<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to urge the President on specific things,&rdquo; she said, describing their Oval Office meeting as an exchange of views rather than a negotiation. She said she was impressed by how closely Trump followed developments in Venezuela and said he was concerned about the well-being of its people, including political prisoners and their families.</p>



<p>Machado said she believed the remnants of what she called a &ldquo;criminal structure&rdquo; that had dominated Venezuela for years would eventually dismantle themselves, paving the way for democratic institutions to be rebuilt. While she offered no details on how or when that would occur, she said that once the transition advanced, Venezuelans would be able to choose their leaders freely, including governors, mayors, and the National Assembly.</p>



<p>Her comments also came amid clear signs of competing courtships of the Trump Administration. Coinciding with her White House visit, CIA Director John Ratcliffe traveled to Caracas to meet Rodr&iacute;guez, the highest-level known U.S. visit since Maduro&rsquo;s removal.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Machado&rsquo;s efforts to win Trump&rsquo;s favor have frustrated some Venezuelans, particularly after the U.S. President dismissed the idea of installing her as the country&rsquo;s leader, arguing she lacked sufficient support in the short term. White House officials have echoed that assessment publicly, even as a <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/miami/news/venezuela-survey-trump-maduro-removal-us-relations-poll/"  target="_blank">poll of Venezuelans</a> released this week by Caracas&#8209;based firm Megan&aacute;lisis found 78% would vote for Machado in a presidential election.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Still, Machado insisted that her goal was not personal power. &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t come here to seek anything for myself,&rdquo; she said.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We have a huge task in front of us to prepare with other teams around the world and in Venezuela to take our government when the right time arrives.&rdquo;</p>



<p>She also portrayed Venezuela&rsquo;s future as closely aligned with U.S. interests. A democratic Venezuela, she said, would become one of the United States&rsquo; closest allies in the hemisphere and a society &ldquo;profoundly pro-America.&rdquo;</p>



<p>For now, the gap remains wide between Trump&rsquo;s rhetoric and Machado&rsquo;s hopes as Trump continues to celebrate cooperation with Rodr&iacute;guez&rsquo;s government on oil and security, deflecting questions about elections and focusing instead on stability and profits.</p>



<p>Machado said she was convinced that those priorities would ultimately converge.</p>



<p>&ldquo;I have no doubt that President Trump, his administration and the people of the United States support democracy, justice and freedom,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;This is a hard process. But the result will be a proud Venezuela&mdash;free, democratic and ready to move forward.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
