		<item>
		<title>One Year Into Trump 2.0, Global Survey Shows More People See China Rising</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346802/european-council-foreign-relations-survey-china-power-trump-geopolitics-diplomacy/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Miranda Jeyaretnam]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Jan 2026 09:55:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Donald Trump]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[overnight]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346802</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Most respondents in almost all the surveyed countries believed that, a year into Trump’s second term, China is on the verge of becoming even more powerful.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346802"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7346802/european-council-foreign-relations-survey-china-power-trump-geopolitics-diplomacy/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/china-us.jpg" alt=""/>



<p>President Donald Trump is &ldquo;making China great again,&rdquo; according to the results of a new <a href="https://ecfr.eu/publication/how-trump-is-making-china-great-again-and-what-it-means-for-europe/"  target="_blank">survey</a> by the European Council on Foreign Relations.</p>



<p>The survey of about 26,000 people found that most respondents in almost all 21 participating countries believed that China will have more global influence over the next decade. Meanwhile, opinions of the U.S. among its traditional allies and adversaries have shifted, while generally expectations of Trump have fallen a year into his presidency.</p>

[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]



<p>&ldquo;A year on from Trump&rsquo;s return, in countries across the globe, many people believe China is on the verge of becoming even more powerful,&rdquo; the report said.</p>



<p>The survey was conducted by ECFR and Oxford University&rsquo;s Europe in a Changing World in November 2025, prior to the <a href="https://time.com/7344628/us-venezuela-trump-maduro-oil-drugs-war-explainer-questions-answered/" >U.S. abduction of former Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro</a> in January. The 21 countries that participated were Brazil, China, India, Russia, South Africa, South Korea, Switzerland, Turkey, the U.K., Ukraine, the U.S., and 10 E.U. countries (Bulgaria, Denmark, Estonia, France, Germany, Hungary, Italy, Poland, Portugal, Spain). The views of the E.U. countries were represented by a simple average of each country&rsquo;s results.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Even before Trump&rsquo;s dramatic intervention in Venezuela, his aggressive &lsquo;America first&rsquo; approach was driving people closer to China,&rdquo; the report said. &ldquo;Paradoxically, his disavowal of the liberal international order may have given people licence to build stronger links to Beijing, since they no longer feel the need to fall in line with a US-led alliance system.&rdquo;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Growing Chinese influence</h2>



<p>South Africa led the view of China as a global leader, with 83% of respondents believing that China will have more global influence over the next decade. That was followed by 72% in Brazil and 63% in Turkey. In the U.S., 54% of respondents held that view, as did an average 53% of respondents across the 10 E.U. countries surveyed. The U.K. had the fewest respondents who held that view, with just 50% believing China&rsquo;s global influence will grow.</p>



<p>But a substantial portion of respondents in each territory, including the U.K., the U.S. and the E.U., also held the view that China&rsquo;s influence would not change over the next decade, because it already has global influence now.</p>



<p>Respondents in several places attributed China&rsquo;s rise to its <a href="https://time.com/7309264/nvidia-trump-china-chips-deal-h20-blackwell-national-security-concerns/" >technological</a> and <a href="https://time.com/7277920/china-manufacturing-us-trump-factory-workers-ai-videos-social-media/" >manufacturing power</a>. Most respondents in China and the E.U. think that China will lead the world in the production of <a href="https://time.com/7288660/shift-east-china-electric-vehicles-economy-technology-trump-tariffs-ai/" >electric vehicles</a> in a decade. That view, as well as the view that China will lead in renewable technology and renewable energy, has become more popular among E.U. and U.S. respondents over the past two years.</p>



<p>Few people seemed concerned about China&rsquo;s rise. Only in Ukraine and <a href="https://time.com/7345772/china-japan-south-korea-relations-export-controls-taiwan/" >South Korea</a> did a majority of respondents consider China as either a rival or an adversary. In fact, a growing number of people view China as an ally or a necessary strategic partner as compared to last year, according to the think tank.</p>



<p>Even in the U.S., China&rsquo;s geopolitical rival, 41% of respondents view China as a necessary partner. And in India, 47% of people see China as an ally or necessary partner. Relations between New Delhi and Beijing have historically been icy, but have <a href="https://time.com/7310270/china-india-us-trump-xi-modi-tariffs-trade-russia-oil/" >warmed in the past year against the backdrop of trade tensions</a> between the U.S. and India straining relations.</p>



<p>Several places also expected their relationship with China to strengthen in the next five years, led by 71% of respondents in South Africa and 52% of respondents in Brazil.</p>



<p>&ldquo;China&rsquo;s rise is seen as something that suits people living in most non-Western countries. Life without a hegemon is how most people appear to imagine the post-American world,&rdquo; the report said. &ldquo;From the perspective of much of the global public, the multipolar order is perfectly compatible with the world of &lsquo;China First.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>



<p>That is in keeping with Beijing&rsquo;s posture. China has sought to &ldquo;work with other countries to &lsquo;democratise international relations&rsquo; by giving non-Western countries more of a voice,&rdquo; the think tank said. Beijing has been <a href="https://time.com/7298254/china-us-diplomacy-military-intervention-taiwan-israel-iran-war-ceasefire/" >positioning itself as a diplomatic alternative</a> to the U.S. and <a href="https://time.com/7301187/china-visa-free-travel-countries-tourism-us-trump-isolation-economy/" >sought to contrast</a> its economic partnerships and participation in multilateral institutions with the <a href="https://time.com/7344810/trump-withdraw-unfccc-climate-impact/" >withdrawal of the U.S. under Trump from international forums</a> and its use of trade measures and the threat&mdash;or use&mdash;of direct military intervention to advance its interests.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We are just 15 days into the year 2026, but the year already has seen black swans and grey rhinos one after the other. Instability and uncertainty are raging all around,&rdquo; China&rsquo;s U.S. envoy Xie Feng <a href="https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3340117/chinas-us-envoy-says-world-faces-stark-choice-2026-opens-instability"  target="_blank">said</a> in an address to the 1,000-member China General Chamber of Commerce on Thursday, in apparent reference to Trump. &ldquo;Where will the world be heading? Humanity is facing a grave choice. Peace or war. Openness or isolation. Cooperation or confrontation.&rdquo;</p>



<p>While a survey published early last year by Singapore-based think tank ISEAS-Yusof Ishak Institute that suggested <a href="https://time.com/7274803/southeast-asia-2025-survey-us-china-trust-asean-iseas-trump/" >more Southeast Asians would choose the U.S. over China</a>, the new survey suggests that many countries do not feel they have to choose between the two powers.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Our data suggest people around the world do not anticipate a bipolar, ideological struggle for primacy,&rdquo; the report said. &ldquo;On the contrary, with the US behaving like just another transactional great power under Trump&mdash;and China establishing itself as a giant of equal stature&mdash;people outside the traditional West seem to expect more room for their own countries to grow and thrive.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Still, some observers have raised concerns that Trump&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7343019/venezuela-trump-oil-china/" >flouting of international norms</a> could encourage Russia and China to more aggressively establish their <a href="https://time.com/7343085/venezuela-trump-us-maduro-china-taiwan-analysis/" >own spheres of influence</a>.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Poorer views of Trump</h2>



<p>Although China is seen as rising in global influence, people don&rsquo;t generally see the U.S. disappearing, even if they don&rsquo;t see its influence rising.</p>



<p>In China, Russia, the U.K., Switzerland, Ukraine, the E.U., South Korea, and even the U.S., a minority of respondents think the U.S. will have more global influence over the next decade than it does today. Around a quarter of respondents in China, Russia, Ukraine, and the U.S. think the U.S. will decline in global influence.</p>



<p>Most countries still see the U.S. as an ally or necessary partner, especially among traditional friends of the U.S., including 89% percent of South Koreans, 88% of Ukrainians, and 76% of Indians.</p>



<p>But across the E.U., just 16% of respondents consider the U.S. an ally whereas 20% of respondents consider it a rival or adversary. In some E.U. member states, nearly 30% of respondents see the U.S. as a rival or adversary, according to the report.</p>



<p>&ldquo;This change may be down to Washington&rsquo;s very public and at times brutal reappraisal of Europe, its politics and its culture,&rdquo; the report said, &ldquo;rather than any real deterioration in American power.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Last year, Trump imposed a series of <a href="https://time.com/7306868/trump-tariffs-tracker-countries-rates-sectors-trade-deals-deadlines-timeline/" >broad tariffs</a> on E.U. imports&mdash;including steep duties on steel, aluminum, automobiles, and other goods&mdash;as well as <a href="https://time.com/7301508/marco-rubio-asean-asia-indo-pacific-security-trump-tariffs-china/" >much of the rest of the world</a> and <a href="https://time.com/7302593/trump-tariffs-eu-trade-deal-china/" >leveraged trade relations with the U.S.</a>&mdash;the world&rsquo;s biggest economy&mdash;to secure deals more favorable to the U.S. Trump has also taken a volatile course in his approach to the <a href="https://time.com/7335666/trump-plan-to-end-russia-ukraine-war-zelensky-response/" >war between Russia and Ukraine</a>, at times publicly criticizing Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky and <a href="https://time.com/7265679/satellites-front-failing-hundreds-dead-fallout-trump-ukraine-aid-pause/" >pausing U.S. military support for Kyiv last March</a>, before reversing course.</p>



<p>The survey results predate the Trump Administration&rsquo;s renewed push in <a href="https://time.com/7344147/greenland-denmark-trump-takeover-independence-purchase-military-nato/" >wanting control of Greenland</a>, which is currently an autonomous territory in the Kingdom of Denmark.</p>



<p><strong>Read More:</strong> <a href="https://time.com/collections/davos-2026/7345543/trump-foreign-policy-second-term/" ><em>How Trump&rsquo;s Foreign Policy Gambits Are Reshaping the World</em></a></p>



<p>The survey suggests that allies of the U.S. no longer see it as reliable. More Ukrainians think that their country&rsquo;s relations with the E.U. will strengthen over the next five years than that with the U.S.</p>



<p>On the other hand, more Russians consider the E.U. an adversary than the U.S. The Russian view of the U.S. as an adversary has fallen dramatically over the past two years, while its view of the U.S. as a necessary partner has risen.</p>



<p>&ldquo;America&rsquo;s traditional enemies fear it less than they once did&mdash;while allies now worry about falling victim to a predatory U.S.,&rdquo; the report said.</p>



<p>Looking forward to the next five years, nearly a quarter of respondents in the E.U. and the U.K. see their relations with the U.S. weakening. That increases to 37% in Switzerland, 35% in China, 28% in South Africa, and 27% in Turkey. Even so, many people see their relations with the U.S. strengthening, led by India where 62% of respondents hold that view.</p>



<p>A year into the second Trump Administration, most countries have lower expectations of Trump than they did a year ago. In the last survey conducted at the end of 2024, 84% of Indians saw Trump&rsquo;s electoral victory as a good thing for their country. That has dropped to just 53% of Indians now.</p>



<p>Last year, a survey by the Pew Research Center showed that an increasing number of respondents&mdash;particularly in Canada and Mexico&mdash;see the U.S. as <a href="https://time.com/7301192/threats-allies-pew-poll-responses-us-china-russia-canada-mexico/" >both a top ally and a major threat</a>. Both countries have not been exempt from Trump&rsquo;s tariffs or threats of U.S. intervention, while countries around the world, especially in the Global South, have felt the effects of the Trump Administration <a href="https://time.com/7298994/usaid-deaths-studies-estimates-foreign-aid-hiv-aids-malaria-sudan/" >slashing U.S. foreign aid</a>.</p>



<p>&ldquo;A year ago Trump was a welcome figure in a Trumpian world: people outside Europe and South Korea held very positive expectations about his return. But this Trumpian moment already appears to be over,&rdquo; the report said. &ldquo;If there is a race for global popularity, America is currently losing to its Indo-Pacific rival.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7346802</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Iran’s Exiled Crown Prince Believes Trump to Be ‘A Man of His Word’</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346706/reza-pahlavi-iran-crown-prince-trump-protests/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Roxana Saberi and Fatemeh Jamalpour]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 15 Jan 2026 21:14:09 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346706</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Reza Pahlavi told TIME that protesters in Iran are counting on the U.S. President to intervene as the regime kills demonstrators by the thousands.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346706"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7346706/reza-pahlavi-iran-crown-prince-trump-protests/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2221035876.jpg" alt="TOPSHOT-FRANCE-IRAN-POLITICS-PORTRAIT-DIPLOMACY"/>



<p>It&rsquo;s been just over a week since Reza Pahlavi, the exiled prince of Iran, set a high-stakes gamble in motion. Along with other activist groups and dissidents, he urged Iranians to take to the streets, betting that the nation had reached <a href="https://time.com/7345555/iran-protests-deaths-us-trump-israel/" >a point of rupture</a> with the Islamic Republic.</p>



<p><strong>Read more:</strong> <a href="https://time.com/7346197/iran-trump-protests-deaths/" ><em>Inside Iran, Protesters Urge Trump to Act: &lsquo;If Nothing Happens, It&rsquo;s a Catastrophe&rsquo;</em></a></p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Protesters have paid a staggering price. By <a href="https://time.com/7345347/iran-protests-death-toll-estimate-thousands/" >some accounts</a>, including an estimate by a Tehran doctor speaking with TIME, at least 20,000 demonstrators were killed by security forces in just three days.</p>



<p>Now, as fear and force push demonstrators indoors, Pahlavi says he and &ldquo;the Iranian people&rdquo; are counting on President Donald Trump to step in to protect them, even after the president<a href="https://apnews.com/article/trump-iran-protesters-executions-195edfa07111be782db71af07b538fdc"  target="_blank"> said</a> on Wednesday he had been told &ldquo;the killing in Iran is stopping.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;The Iranian people see President Trump as a man of his word and believe he will follow through with the promise he made to defend them,&rdquo; Pahlavi told TIME on Thursday in written responses to a series of questions.</p>



<p><strong>Read more: </strong><a href="https://time.com/7346661/trump-iran-military-strikes-diplomacy-sanctions/" ><em>For Trump, a Path Forward on Iran That Goes Beyond Bombs</em></a></p>



<p>Several Iranians told TIME they were emboldened by Trump&rsquo;s repeated warnings, dating back to <a href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/115824439366264186"  target="_blank">Jan. 2,</a> that if Iranian authorities killed protesters, &ldquo;We are locked and loaded and ready to go.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Based on conversations with Iranians and chants such as &ldquo;O&rsquo; king of Iran, come back to Iran, the mullahs have trashed the country&rdquo; that echoed across the rallies, many were also encouraged to march for Pahlavi. When asked if it was irresponsible to call Iranians into the streets without protection, Pahlavi placed the blame on Iran&rsquo;s Supreme Leader, his regime and &ldquo;their supporters in the West.&rdquo;<br><br>&ldquo;They have the lives of tens of thousands of my bravest compatriots on their hands,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;But we will ensure their sacrifice is not in vain and we will win.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump has not offered details about how the U.S. may or may not respond to the killings.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;My team and I are in touch with the administration,&rdquo; Pahlavi said, though he declined to discuss specifics of what he had asked the Administration for, and what, if anything, it had committed to do.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;We do not need foreign boots on the ground, but we do need action that prevents the IRGC [the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps] and security forces from continuing mass violence against the people,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;People need help to level the playing field.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump has been reluctant to lend his full support to Pahlavi, however. &#8220;He seems very nice, but I don&#8217;t know how he&#8217;d play within his own country,&#8221; the president&nbsp;said. &#8220;I don&#8217;t know whether or not his country would accept his leadership, and certainly if they would, that would be fine with me.&#8221;</p>



<p>Pahlavi has spent decades casting himself in this role. Iranians inside and outside Iran told TIME that in recent years, his popularity has surged, in part because no other opposition figures have the profile to unite and lead them. But Pahlavi remains polarizing. Some Iranians remember his father&rsquo;s reign as an era of development and close ties with the West; others recall authoritarianism and the notorious SAVAK secret police.</p>



<p>The 65-year-old laid out his plans for a secular post-Islamic Republic transition in a <a href="https://fund.nufdiran.org/projects/ipp/research/emergency-phase-booklet/"  target="_blank">roadmap</a> published online last July. The plan centers on a council with &ldquo;major interim state functions&rdquo;, its members appointed by him, alongside executive and judicial bodies whose leaders would be installed or removed with his approval.</p>



<p>After the regime falls, the plan calls for a referendum on the future system of government, either a &ldquo;democratic monarchy&rdquo; or a &ldquo;democratic republic.&rdquo; His role, he said, was to remain impartial and not &ldquo;tip the scales&rdquo; in favor of either.&nbsp;</p>



<p>When asked if and how he would govern the country if people called upon him, he responded: &ldquo;The people must vote and decide on this.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Karim Parwizi, a member of the leadership of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran, an opposition group based in northern Iraq, argued that the roadmap leaves too much power in Pahlavi&rsquo;s hands.</p>



<p>&#8220;He is presented as the one who decides everything,&rdquo; he told TIME. &ldquo;That suggests the foundations of another dictatorship are being laid.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Pahlavi was born to be a king&mdash;the crown prince, long-awaited after Mohammad Reza Shah&rsquo;s two failed marriages, before his marriage to Farah Diba.&nbsp;</p>



<p>That trajectory was abruptly cut short.&nbsp;At 18, while Pahlavi was training to fly fighter jets at Reese Air Force Base in Lubbock, Texas, the 1979 Islamic Revolution toppled his father&rsquo;s rule.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-1960262256.jpg" alt="Coronation Of Shah Of Iran" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>Pahlavi went on to earn a bachelor&rsquo;s degree in political science at the University of Southern California, got married, and now has three adult daughters. Living mostly in Los Angeles and the Washington D.C. area, he has continued to call for the fall of the Islamic Republic.</p>



<p>It is difficult, however, to determine the exact extent of his popular support among Iran&rsquo;s roughly 92 million people. </p>



<p>&ldquo;My view of it is that Reza Pahlavi is just simply being the leader to coordinate the removal of the regime,&rdquo; a resident of Shiraz, who heeded Pahlavi&rsquo;s calls to protest last week, told TIME on condition of anonymity. He added that he &ldquo;wouldn&rsquo;t mind if he becomes the next shah.&rdquo;</p>



<p>A <a href="https://gamaan.org/2025/08/20/analytical-report-on-iranians-political-preferences-in-2024/"  target="_blank">2024 survey</a> by the Netherlands-based research group Gamaan found that if Iran were to hold a free and fair election, Pahlavi would be the &ldquo;preferred candidate&rdquo; among more than 30 political and civil society figures.</p>



<p>&ldquo;He has symbolic importance in capturing the popular rejection of the Islamic Republic, and this owes a great deal to the nostalgia for his father and grandfather&rsquo;s periods,&rdquo; said Vali Nasr, a professor at Johns Hopkins University&rsquo;s School of Advanced International Studies. &ldquo;But I am not convinced his support is broad based and will be directed into a meaningful political movement.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Critics have said the exiled prince and his team have not done enough to unite opposition factions, both inside and outside Iran, or to reach out to minority ethnic groups, which are thought to make up about half of the country&rsquo;s population.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;Pahlavi and his colleagues have shown no indication of dialogue with ethnic minorities, not only Kurds but also Baluch, Turks and Arabs,&rdquo; said Amjad Hossein Panahi, a political member of the opposition Komala Party of Iranian Kurdistan. &ldquo;There is no meaningful difference between him and the current regime.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Shirin Ebadi, Iran&rsquo;s 2003 Nobel Peace Prize laureate, hopes Pahlavi, working alongside other groups, can help manage any transition. &ldquo;Let the regime fall,&rdquo; she said.</p>



<p>Many US government officials also see Pahlavi as the most viable opposition figure, a US-based analyst explained, &ldquo;partly because his group and the regime have spent so much time discrediting other opposition figures.&rdquo;<br><br>She spoke on condition of anonymity because, she claimed, some of Pahlavi&rsquo;s supporters in the Iranian diaspora are &ldquo;bullies.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Pahlavi, however, presents himself as a unifier. Many in Iran&rsquo;s opposition &ldquo;know only I can help lead the transition to democracy.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;That,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;is why I am stepping forward to lead.&rdquo;</p>



<p></p>



<p><em>Correction, Jan. 15</em></p>



<p><em>The original headline for this story mischaracterized what Reza Pahlavi said about President Trump. He said he believes Trump is &#8220;a man of his word,&#8221; not that he was appealing to Trump to be one.</em></p>



<p></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
