		<item>
		<title>María Machado Gives Trump Her Nobel Peace Prize as She Presses Him to Support Democracy in Venezuela</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346654/machado-trump-meeting-nobel-prize-venezuela/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Brian Bennett]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 15 Jan 2026 19:03:36 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venezuela]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346654</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Machado has suggested she might give Trump her Nobel Peace Prize medal at the meeting.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346654"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7346654/machado-trump-meeting-nobel-prize-venezuela/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255800926.jpg" alt="US-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-TRUMP"/>



<p>Now he has his Nobel Peace Prize&ndash;sort of.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Venezuelan opposition leader <a href="https://time.com/7343295/venezuela-machado-trump-nobel-peace-prize/" >Mar&iacute;a Corina Machado</a> presented President Donald Trump with the Nobel Peace Prize medal she was awarded in December, she told reporters on Capitol Hill Thursday. Machado said she made the presentation when she met with Trump for lunch at the White House earlier in the day.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>&ldquo;I presented the President of the United States the medal&mdash; the Nobel Peace Prize,&rdquo; Machado said. When she made the presentation, she said she told him a story of a similar medal with George Washington&rsquo;s face on it that General Marquis de Lafayette, the French military officer who helped win the American Revolution, had given Simon Bolivar, who helped liberate Venezuela and five other Latin American countries from Spanish rule. She said she called Trump, as the American President, the &ldquo;heir&rdquo; of Washington and told him: &ldquo;The people of Bolivar are giving back to the heir of Washington a medal&mdash;in this case a medal of the Nobel Peace Prize and the recognition of his unique commitment to our freedom.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Trump has repeatedly said he deserves the award and his supporters have criticized Machado for accepting it. The day Machado won the award, she called Trump at the White House to tell him she was dedicating the prize to him. Machado told Fox News host Sean Hannity last week that she would like to tell him personally that the Venezuelan people &ldquo;want to give it to him and share it with him.&rdquo; Soon after, the Norwegian Nobel Institute released a statement asserting that its prizes &ldquo;cannot be revoked, shared, or transferred.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Machado&rsquo;s main objective on Thursday was to impress upon Trump the importance of transitioning Venezuela from an autocracy to a government elected by Venezuelans that protected individual freedoms.</p>



<p>It may be an uphill climb. Since Trump ordered the arrest of the country&rsquo;s dictator Nicolas Maduro in a military raid on Jan. 3, he has signaled support for Maduro&rsquo;s ally Delcy Rodriguez as Venezuela&rsquo;s interim President, calling her &ldquo;terrific,&rdquo; while slighting Machado as not respected enough by Venezuelans to be their next leader. In the nearly two weeks since Maduro&rsquo;s ouster, Rodriguez&rsquo;s government has sent armed militias into the streets to <a href="https://time.com/7345598/venezuela-militias-violence-maduro-trump/" >search phones and arrest people </a>who expressed support for Maduro&rsquo;s capture.</p>



<p>Trump and Secretary of State Marco Rubio want what&rsquo;s left of Maduro&rsquo;s autocratic government to fulfill U.S. demands to control Venezuela&rsquo;s oil output and to stop drug smuggling.  He hasn&rsquo;t said publicly when he wants the current government to agree to allow free elections in the country. Maduro&rsquo;s government refused to step down in July 2024 when Maduro lost the country&rsquo;s presidential election. Machado&rsquo;s ally Edmundo Gonz&aacute;lez won that election after Machado was banned from the ballot.</p>



<p>As the high-stakes meeting was underway, White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt said Trump was &ldquo;looking forward&rdquo; to having &ldquo;a good and positive discussion.&rdquo; Leavitt praised Machado as &ldquo;a remarkable and brave voice for many of the people in&rdquo; Venezuela. </p>



<p></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
