		<item>
		<title>Denmark Beefs Up Military Presence in Greenland Amid &#8216;Fundamental Disagreement&#8217; With U.S.</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Nik Popli]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 14 Jan 2026 20:35:48 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Denmark]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346397</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Denmark's foreign minister said it was committing "not dogsleds, but ships, drones, fighter jets" to Greenland.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346397"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7346397/denmark-greenland-military-presence-nato-trump/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255676591.jpg" alt="Trump Reasserts Greenland Claim As Diplomats Arrive In US"/>



<p>Denmark&rsquo;s foreign minister said on Wednesday that a &ldquo;fundamental disagreement&rdquo; with U.S. President Donald Trump over the future of Greenland remained unresolved after high-level talks in Washington, even as Denmark and NATO allies moved to increase their military presence in the Arctic territory amid rising tensions.</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Speaking at a press conference after meeting with U.S. Vice President J.D. Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Denmark&rsquo;s foreign minister Lars L&oslash;kke Rasmussen described the discussions as &ldquo;frank but also constructive,&rdquo; but made clear that Denmark and Greenland firmly reject the Trump Administration&rsquo;s continued efforts to control the semiautonomous island.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;The President has made his view clear, and we have a different position,&rdquo; Rasmussen said. &ldquo;Ideas that would not respect the territorial integrity of the Kingdom of Denmark and the right of self-determination of the Greenlandic people are totally unacceptable.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The high-profile meeting came as Denmark and its NATO partners are taking visible steps to reinforce their presence in Greenland. In Copenhagen, Denmark&rsquo;s defense minister, Troels Lund Poulsen, announced that Denmark would increase military activity in and around Greenland, citing an increasingly unpredictable security environment. Rasmussen told reporters in Washington that Denmark was reinforcing security in the Arctic &ldquo;by committing additional funds for military capabilities&mdash;not dogsleds, but ships, drones, fighter jets, etc.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Several European NATO allies confirmed that they were also sending personnel to the island. Sweden&rsquo;s prime minister, Ulf Kristersson, said that officers from the Swedish Armed Forces had arrived in Greenland to prepare for activities connected to a Danish military exercise, Operation Arctic Endurance. Norway said it would send two military personnel to explore further cooperation with allies.</p>



<p>Germany&rsquo;s Defense Ministry said it was dispatching a reconnaissance team of 13 military personnel to Greenland for an exploration mission from January 15 to 17. The goal, the ministry said, was to assess possible contributions to regional security, including maritime surveillance.</p>



<p>The moves underscore growing concern in Europe that Trump&rsquo;s rhetoric risks destabilizing relations within NATO.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We are definitely ready to do more,&rdquo; Rasmussen added.</p>



<p>Rasmussen was joined in the discussions with the White House by Greenland&rsquo;s foreign minister Vivian Motzfeldt, who said that while Greenland was open to strengthening cooperation with the United States on security, that did not mean it was interested in being owned by Washington.</p>



<p>&ldquo;We have shown where our limits are,&rdquo; Motzfeldt said. &ldquo;It is in everyone&rsquo;s interest to find the right path&mdash;but that path does not include ownership.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The meeting in Washington was requested by officials from Greenland and Denmark amid an escalating dispute fueled by Trump&rsquo;s repeated insistence that the United States must acquire Greenland &ldquo;one way or another&rdquo; for national security reasons. Greenland is a semiautonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, which retains responsibility for the island&rsquo;s defense and foreign policy.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255656501.jpg" alt="US-DENMARK-GREENLAND-POLITICS-DIPLOMACY" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>In recent days, Trump has argued that NATO should support a U.S. takeover of the island, warning that anything short of American control would leave Greenland vulnerable to China or Russia.</p>



<p>&ldquo;NATO becomes far more formidable and effective with Greenland in the hands of the United States,&rdquo; Trump wrote on social media hours before the talks. &ldquo;<a href="https://time.com/7346104/trump-greenland-annexation-threat-us-control/" >Anything less than that is unacceptable</a>.&rdquo;</p>



<p><strong>Read more:</strong> <em><a href="https://time.com/7346324/greenland-trump-polls-annexation-denmark/" >Americans Don&rsquo;t Want Greenland. Trump Is Convinced He Can Change That</a></em></p>



<p>Denmark and Greenland, both part of the NATO alliance, strongly dispute that claim. &ldquo;According to our intelligence, we haven&#8217;t had a Chinese warship in Greenland for a decade or so,&rdquo; Rasmussen said at the press conference. &ldquo;There is not an instant threat from China or Russia that we cannot accommodate.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Rasmussen said Denmark believed Greenland&rsquo;s long-term security could be ensured &ldquo;inside the current framework,&rdquo; noting that the United States already maintains a military presence on the island under a 1951 defense agreement that allows Washington to establish and expand bases with the consent of Danish and Greenlandic authorities.</p>



<p>&ldquo;The U.S. has already wide military access to Greenland,&rdquo; Rasmussen said. &ldquo;We wish to hear if the U.S. had any further request to make in this aspect. We would examine any such request constructively.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Despite the sharp disagreement, the two sides agreed to establish a high-level working group to explore whether some of Trump&rsquo;s stated security concerns could be addressed without crossing what Denmark calls its &ldquo;red lines.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;The group, in our view, should focus on how to address the American security concerns, while at the same time respecting the red lines of the Kingdom of Denmark,&rdquo; Rasmussen said. The group is expected to hold its first meeting within weeks.</p>



<p>Asked about his suggestion to acquire Greenland by force, Trump told reporters on Wednesday, &ldquo;I never said that.&rdquo;</p>



<p>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t rely on Denmark being able to fend themselves off,&rdquo; he added. &ldquo;They were talking about they would put an extra dog&#8211;and they were serious about this&#8211; they put an extra dog sled there last month, they added a second dog sled. That&rsquo;s not going to do the trick.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Greenland&rsquo;s prime minister, Jens-Frederik Nielsen, <a href="https://time.com/7345949/greenland-denmark-trump/" >said on Tuesday</a> that if Greenland were forced to choose, &ldquo;we choose Denmark. We choose NATO. We choose the Kingdom of Denmark. We choose the EU.&rdquo; Trump responded by saying he did not know Nielsen and that his position would be &ldquo;a big problem for him.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Greenland&rsquo;s strategic importance has increased as climate change melts Arctic ice, opening shorter shipping routes to Asia and raising interest in the island&rsquo;s untapped reserves of critical minerals used in advanced technologies. Trump has also described Greenland as vital to his proposed &ldquo;Golden Dome&rdquo; missile defense system.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7346397</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Gaza Is Entering Second Stage of Cease-Fire Plan, Says U.S., as Committee Leader Is Named</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346341/gaza-phase-two-ceasefire-committee-members-peace-board/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Olivia-Anne Cleary and Callum Sutherland]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 14 Jan 2026 19:41:47 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Israel-Hamas War]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346341</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The mediators of the cease-fire deal announced that the committee will be headed by Ali Shaath, a former deputy minister in the Palestinian Authority.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346341"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module video-2" data-src="https://time.com/7346341/gaza-phase-two-ceasefire-committee-members-peace-board/" data-widget-id="SB_4" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255541531.jpg" alt="Winter-Winds-Batter-Gaza-Tent-Shelters"/>



<p>The U.S. announced the launch of &ldquo;Phase Two&rdquo; of President Donald Trump&rsquo;s <a href="https://time.com/7327675/trump-israel-gaza-deal-interview/" >Gaza cease-fire plan </a>on Wednesday, officially embarking on the &ldquo;demilitarization, technocratic governance, and reconstruction&rdquo; of the territory.</p>



<p>Trump&rsquo;s Special Envoy Steve Witkoff <a href="https://x.com/SEPeaceMissions/status/2011478211075391845"  target="_blank">confirmed</a> a Palestinian Administration titled the National Committee for the Administration of Gaza (NCAG) will be established to oversee the rebuilding efforts. Wifkoff also emphasized that the U.S. &ldquo;expects Hamas to comply fully with its obligations&rdquo; and called for the militant group to release the body of Ran Gvili, the final deceased hostage. He warned a lack of compliance would bring &ldquo;serious consequences.&rdquo;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Witkoff did not offer further information as to who would be on the committee and what the reconstruction of Gaza might look like.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The White House did not immediately respond to TIME&rsquo;s request for further information.</p>



<p>Egypt, Qatar, and Turkey, the mediators of the cease-fire deal, in a joint <a href="https://mofa.gov.qa/en/latest-articles/statements/joint-statement-from-the-mediators-on-the-formation-of-the-palestinian-technocratic-committee-to-administer-the-gaza-strip"  target="_blank">statement</a> shared after Witkoff&rsquo;s update, announced that the committee will be headed by Ali Shaath, a former deputy minister in the Palestinian Authority. The countries expressed hope that this next phase of the deal will bring &ldquo;security, stability, and a dignified life&rdquo; for the Palestinian people.</p>



<p>Hussein Al-Sheikh, the vice president of the Palestine Liberation Organization, also welcomed news of the progress in Gaza.</p>



<p>Al-Sheikh <a href="https://x.com/HusseinSheikhpl/status/2011445660499775945"  target="_blank">stated</a> the importance of not creating any arrangements that might cause further division, while highlighting the need for local figures to work with the United States &ldquo;and relevant partners to take decisive steps in the West Bank in parallel with the transitional phase in Gaza.&rdquo;</p>



<p>Phase One of the cease-fire deal faced a number of challenges. Hamas, which has ruled over Gaza for 18 years and has yet to disarm, did not return the remains of the final <a href="https://time.com/7283392/tal-shoham-freed-hamas-hostage-gaza-essay/" >hostage</a>. The Israeli airstrikes that have taken place since the cease-fire came into effect in October have also halted progress.</p>



<p>It&rsquo;s understood that throughout Phase Two, the committee will handle the day-to-day items in Gaza and will be overseen by the Trump-led &ldquo;Gaza Board of Peace.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The members of the board have yet to be confirmed. Reports have named various high-profile figures&mdash;such as former United Nations Middle East envoy, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/13/world/middleeast/gaza-palestinian-committee.html"  target="_blank">Nickolay Mladenov</a>, and former U.K. Prime Minister Tony Blair&mdash;as potential committee members. There have also been multiple reports that the current U.K. Prime Minister, Keir Starmer&mdash;who has<a href="https://time.com/7318214/trump-starmer-us-uk-tech-prosperity-deal-signed/" > cultivated a strong, working relationship with Trump</a>&mdash;has been asked to serve on the board.</p>



<p>TIME has been told that conversations regarding the make-up of the board are ongoing, but Starmer has yet to receive a formal invite.</p>



<p>According to Reuters, an announcement regarding the Board of Peace is set to be made at DAVOS next week.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">7346341</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Inside Iran, Protesters Urge Trump to Act: ‘If Nothing Happens, It’s a Catastrophe’</title>
		<link>https://time.com/7346197/iran-trump-protests-deaths/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Kay Armin Serjoie]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 14 Jan 2026 17:44:55 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News Desk]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://time.com/?p=7346197</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Iranians say many protesters are pinning their hopes on President Donald Trump following through on his threats against Iran’s rulers.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<aside class="right-rail__container right-rail__container--ad"><div class="right-rail__ad__wrapper right-rail__module"><div class="right-rail__ad" id="right-rail__ad-7346197"></div></div>
<div class="OUTBRAIN right-rail__outbrain right-rail__module" data-src="https://time.com/7346197/iran-trump-protests-deaths/" data-widget-id="SB_2" data-ob-template="timemag"></div></aside>

<img decoding="async" class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-featured-media" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/iran-protests-001.jpg" alt="Protests Against The Regime In Iran"/>



<p>Despite an almost total communications blackout, a small number of Iranians have managed to send messages out of the country. They describe <a href="https://time.com/7345347/iran-protests-death-toll-estimate-thousands/" >mounting civilian deaths</a> and streets awash with blood&mdash;and say many protesters are pinning their hopes on President Donald Trump following through on his threats against Iran&rsquo;s rulers.</p>



<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s the only thing they&rsquo;re thinking about,&rdquo; said a resident of Tehran&rsquo;s Marzdaran neighborhood.&nbsp;</p>
[time-brightcove not-tgx=&#8221;true&#8221;]




<p>Another resident, from the capital&rsquo;s affluent Niavaran district, said protesters see <a href="https://time.com/7345744/trump-iran-protesters-strike-explainer/" >outside intervention</a> as their only remaining option. &ldquo;People know they won&#8217;t be able to beat them without help,&rdquo; they said.</p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7345555/iran-protests-deaths-us-trump-israel/" ><em>What&rsquo;s Happening in Iran Right Now, Explained</em></a></p>



<p>Only days ago, city streets were crowded with demonstrators chanting for the downfall of the government. Now, according to residents and phone footage that has circulated online, those same streets are patrolled by trucks mounted with heavy machine guns.</p>



<p>&ldquo;If Uncle doesn&#8217;t do something it&#8217;s over. They will just go on killing people until no one&rsquo;s left,&rdquo; the Niavaran district resident said, referring to Trump as &ldquo;Uncle&rdquo; out of fear that Iranian intelligence might somehow be monitoring Starlink, the satellite internet system that circumvents the state&rsquo;s blackout.</p>



<p>Trump, meanwhile, continues to raise hopes. &ldquo;Help is on its way,&rdquo; the President wrote on Truth Social on Tuesday, in the most explicit promise of intervention since Jan. 2., when he first warned Iran&rsquo;s authorities against attacking Iranians. &ldquo;Keep protesting &#8211; take over your institutions,&rdquo; he said, adding that those responsible would &ldquo;pay a big price.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The post was reported on Persian-language satellite news channels, which have remained available despite the internet blackout. &ldquo;Literally 9 or 10 people called, and said, &lsquo;Good news&mdash;Trump said help is on the way,&rdquo; said a man who had traveled out of Iran on Wednesday.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Everyone is waiting for an attack, an attack that will weaken the suppression system,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;If that happens the whole country will go back on the streets.&rdquo;</p>



<p>He described a capital where consumer goods had grown scarce&mdash;it took two hours to find eggs&mdash;and residents had been instructed to be indoors by 4 p.m. &ldquo;The city looks frightening. After 3 or 4 pm, it&#8217;s deserted.&#8221;</p>



<p><strong>Read more</strong>: <a href="https://time.com/7345744/trump-iran-protesters-strike-explainer/" ><em>Will the U.S. Strike Iran? The Factors Shaping Trump&rsquo;s Decision</em></a></p>



<p>Iranians say the massive loss of life&mdash;which estimates suggest is more than 10,000 killed&mdash;has kept many indoors.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;Fear is back,&rdquo; said a resident of Yasuj, a city in southwestern Iran. &ldquo;On Thursday night they started shooting into the crowds. I saw someone shot right in front of me.&rdquo; A resident of Tehran&rsquo;s Yusefabad district said Monday that the streets were more empty now. &ldquo;Most people are afraid to go out any more.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The crackdown, they say, is being carried out primarily by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps and its Basij militia&mdash;forces that have crushed protests for decades. &ldquo;They&rsquo;re standing at every junction,&rdquo; said one woman from the capital&#8217;s Yusefabad district. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s martial law. They&rsquo;re shooting in the air just to remind everyone they&rsquo;re in control of the streets.&rdquo; </p>



<p>The Guards and the Basij began replacing the regular police and its specialised anti-riot units from Jan. 8. It is not clear if the replacement was due to the inability of the police to suppress the protests, or reports of defections. In one instance a video emerged from the western city of Abdanan, where the local police were no longer on the streets, but rather standing on the roof of their station and waving at the massive crowds of protestors.</p>



<p>In Yasuj, the resident said police units vanished from the streets after reports of defections. &ldquo;But they were all arrested, the police have practically withdrawn from the streets,&rdquo; he said. There have been no eyewitness accounts of police patrols in Iranian cities in recent days.</p>



<p>&ldquo;Everyone is so restless, so hopeless,&rdquo; said the man in Marzdaran, a neighborhood in northwest Tehran. The bodies in the street are not strangers, he added.  &ldquo;Many people have lost a relative, or a close friend. They are just killing, killing, killing.&rdquo;</p>



<p>The accounts are supported by footage of security forces shooting assault rifles into crowds, bursts from truck-mounted heavy machine guns in residential streets, and bodies lined up by the hundreds at a morgue.<strong> </strong>&ldquo;In Nourabad and Dehdasht&hellip; they are still killing&rdquo;, the resident of Yasuj said, naming nearby smaller cities.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-gutenberg-custom-blocks-inline-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://api.time.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/GettyImages-2255209397.jpg" alt="Protests in Iran January 2026" alignment="center"/><p class="article_header"></p><p class="article_subheading"></p><p class="article_text"></p></figure>



<p>The communications blackout has deepened the sense of isolation. Iranian authorities have shut down the internet during past protests, but this time they also cut off cell phone networks, SMS messaging, and landlines&mdash;severing Iranians not only from the outside world, but from one another.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&ldquo;If people in different cities could hear what others are doing, they might be able to get heart from each other,&rdquo; said the Yasuj resident. &ldquo;But now they just feel they are all alone.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Starlink remains the sole breach in the internet blackout. Though illegal in Iran, the satellite dishes were <a href="https://time.com/6249365/iran-elon-musk-starlink-protests/" >smuggled</a> in during the last major protests. Today, tens of thousands are operating across the country, often extending Wi-Fi signals across entire buildings or neighborhoods while concealing the origin of the signal. Several activists confirmed Tuesday that Starlink, owned by Elon Musk, has suspended subscription fees and updated its software to evade jamming.</p>



<p>Those managing to send messages abroad may not represent all Iranians. Before the recent violence, polls suggested the regime could rely on the support of only about 20 percent of the population. Yet Iran is also deeply nationalistic, and even among the remaining 80 percent, support for foreign military intervention has historically been uncertain. That hesitation was visible last June, during Israel&rsquo;s so-called 12-day war with Iran&mdash;while the strikes targeted military and nuclear sites, they also killed hundreds of civilians, triggering backlash and unease.</p>



<p>&ldquo;It&#8217;s different this time,&rdquo; the resident of Yasuj maintained. &ldquo;It&#8217;s a one-sided war against a bloodthirsty regime. Many have set their hopes on Trump. And it&rsquo;s understandable. If something, somehow doesn&#8217;t happen&#8230; it&#8217;ll be a catastrophe.&rdquo;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
